{"title_page": "HMS Fearless (L10)", "text_new": "{{short description|Royal Navy ship that served from 1965 until 2002}}\n{{other ships|HMS Fearless}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=HMS Fearless (L10) off North Carolina 1996.JPEG\n|Ship caption=HMS ''Fearless'' off North Carolina, 9 May 1996\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United Kingdom\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|UK|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Fearless''\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=Harland and Wolff, Belfast\n|Ship laid down= 25 July 1962\n|Ship launched=19 December 1963\n|Ship sponsor=Lady Hull, wife of [[Richard Hull|Field Marshal Sir Richard Hull]]\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned= 25 November 1965\n|Ship decommissioned= 18 March 2002\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship identification=*[[Pennant number|Pennant]] L10\n*{{IMO Number|4907177}}\n|Ship fate=Scrapped [[Ghent]] harbour (BE) 2008\n|Ship motto=*''Explicit Nomen''\n*(\"The name says it all\")\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Fearless|landing platform dock}}\n|Ship displacement=12,120 tons (full load)\n|Ship length= {{convert|520|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|80|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught={{convert|21|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship propulsion=2 \u00d7 [[English Electric]] 2 shaft geared [[steam turbine]]s. {{convert|22000|shp|abbr=on}} total\n|Ship speed={{convert|21|kn|km/h}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship capacity=\t\n|Ship complement= 580\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*2 \u00d7 [[BMARC]] GAM B01 20&nbsp;mm. single mounts\n*2 \u00d7 [[Phalanx CIWS]]\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship aircraft=Landing platform for up to 5 [[Westland Sea King|Sea King]] helicopters.\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''HMS ''Fearless'' (L10)''' was a [[Royal Navy]] amphibious assault ship that served from 1965 until 2002. One of two {{sclass-|Fearless|landing platform dock}}s, she was based in [[HMNB Portsmouth|HMNB ''Portsmouth'']] and saw service around the world over her 37-year life. She was the last steam-powered surface ship in the Royal Navy.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080726093933/http://www.btinternet.com/~warship/Today/intrepid.htm]</ref>\n\n==Role==\n\n{{main| Fearless-class landing platform dock}}\n\nThe landing platform docks (LPD) supported a [[Royal Marines]] amphibious assault force and provided a platform for the Headquarters capability prior to, and during, the assault phase. The Royal Marines served aboard as the 4th Assault Squadron. The Squadron included crew for the four [[Landing Craft Utility|LCU]]s, four [[Landing craft of the Royal Marines#LCVP Mk2|LCVP]]s and the Beach Party, which was equipped with a [[Land Rover]], a Bedford 4-ton truck, two tractor units\u2014one a track layer, the other equipped with a bucket\u2014and a Centurion [[BARV]]. The squadron also had duties aboard, (ensuring equipment and troops got to shore as they were needed), radio operators and administration.\n\n==Service==\n''Fearless'' was the first purpose-built LPD used by the Royal Navy. Built in [[Belfast]] at the [[Harland and Wolff]] yard, she was launched in 1963 before undergoing trials and commissioning in 1965.\n\nFollowing commissioning, her first operational tasking was acting as a command platform for British Counter-Terrorism operations in [[Colony of Aden|Aden]], operating [[Royal Air Force]] aircraft and the [[Irish Guards]] prior to the British withdrawal as Flag of a 25 platform task group. Following the Aden experiences, she was the venue for talks between [[Harold Wilson]] and [[Ian Smith]] in 1968, over the future of [[Rhodesia]]. The latter had unilaterally declared independence([[Unilateral Declaration of Independence (Rhodesia)|UDI]]) from Britain, owing to Britain's insistence on the removal of white minority rule.\n\nBetween 1969 and 1970 she was commanded by Captain [[John Gerard-Pearse]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mackie|first1=Colin|title=Senior Royal Navy Appointments from 1865|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Senior%20Royal%20Navy%20Appointments%201865-.pdf|website=Gulabin|publisher=Colin Mackie|accessdate=18 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1972, ''Fearless'' ferried several Centurion [[AVRE]] [[demolition vehicle]]s, derived from the [[Centurion tank]], to [[Northern Ireland]] to be deployed there as part of [[Operation Motorman]].<ref name=\"Osprey\">Osprey Publishing: Centurion Universal Tank 1943\u20132003 {{ISBN|1-84176-387-X}}{{page needed|date=October 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Fearless'' featured in the 1977 [[James Bond]] film ''[[The Spy Who Loved Me (film)|The Spy Who Loved Me]]'' as the ship that picks up Bond's escape pod. The filming took place the previous year near the island of Malta.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7024769.stm|title=HMS Fearless heads for scrapyard|work=BBC News|date=2 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:HMS Fearless, San Carlos, 1982.JPG|thumb|left|''Fearless'' in [[San Carlos, Falkland Islands|San Carlos]], during the [[Falklands War]]]]\n[[File:Sounds on board HMS Fearless.ogg|alt=Sounds on board HMS Fearless during the Falklands War.|thumb|Sounds on board of HMS ''Fearless'' during the Falklands War.]]\n\n''Fearless'' was part of the [[British naval forces in the Falklands War|British naval force]] committed to [[Operation Corporate]], the 1982 [[Falklands War]]. Fitted with modern satellite communications equipment, it hosted the staff of amphibious force commander [[Commodore (Royal Navy)|Commodore]] Michael Clapp (Commodore Amphibious Warfare (COMAW)), and Commanding Officer [[3 Commando Brigade]], [[Brigadier]] [[Julian Thompson (Royal Marines officer)|Julian Thompson]] and his staff, as well as elements of the landing force. As a result of the conflict, Royal Marine Coxswain Corporal Alan White received a commendation from the Task Force Commander, Admiral Sir [[John Fieldhouse, Baron Fieldhouse|John Fieldhouse]], for his part in rescuing 41 crew from {{HMS|Antelope|F170|6}} using Foxtrot 7, one of four LCVP landing craft carried by Fearless. Foxtrot 7 is now located in the Royal Marines Museum in Portsmouth, with detailed accounts from Corporal Alan White of the missions he took part in, including the landings at San Carlos.\n\nShe was placed out of commission for three years in 1985 prior to a two-year refit at Devonport, recommissioning in 1991. During this refit, her 1940s-vintage [[Bofors 40 mm gun|40mm Bofors]] cannon and 1960s-vintage [[Sea Cat missile|Sea Cat]] anti-aircraft missile launchers were replaced by 20&nbsp;mm BMARC and [[Phalanx CIWS]] guns.\n\nFrom 1991 until 1995 she supported the sea training phase of initial officer training, undertaken at [[Britannia Royal Naval College]], as part of the Dartmouth Training Squadron.\n\nShe was due to undertake an operation in the Gulf, but that was handed to {{HMS|Ocean|L12|6}} in 2000. Her last major duty was to take part in amphibious exercises shortly before decommissioning.\n\n===Decommissioned===\n[[File:HMS Fearless (L10) 2001.jpg|thumb|HMS ''Fearless'' in the Indian Ocean, 16 November 2001.]]\n\n''Fearless'' was decommissioned in 2002 and awaited disposal in [[Fareham]] Creek, [[Hampshire]], moored alongside her [[sister ship]] {{HMS|Intrepid|L11|2}}. In October 2007, it was reported that ''Fearless'' was to be scrapped in Belgium,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7024769.stm|title=HMS Fearless heads for scrapyard|work=BBC News|date=2 October 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/EquipmentAndLogistics/FalklandsCommandShipToBeRecycled.htm|title=Falklands command ship to be recycled|work=Ministry of Defence|date=2 October 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20120817092501/http://www.mod.uk:80/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/EquipmentAndLogistics/FalklandsCommandShipToBeRecycled.htm|archive-date=17 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nfive years after the vessel was officially mothballed in Portsmouth. On 17 December 2007, ''Fearless'' was towed to [[Ghent]] in Belgium to be broken up.\n\nThis was the first warship successfully exported for recycling by any western government that fully complied with international agreements and the principles concerning environmentally sound management of waste.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.edisposals.com/docs/webversionfearless.pdf|title=Recycling of HMS Fearless|publisher=edisposals.com}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nReplacement LPDs {{HMS|Albion|L14|2}} and {{HMS|Bulwark|L15|2}} were ordered during the 1990s. They were commissioned in 2003.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.hmsfearless.co.uk/ HMS Fearless Association]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080110111551/http://www.f913westhinder.be/ Pictures of HMS Fearless being broken up]\n*[http://www.axfordsabode.org.uk/pdf-docs/fearles1.pdf HMS Fearless Book 1970\u20131972]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110207112500/http://hmsfearless-hmsintrepid.com/ HMS Fearless Operational and manning arrangements]\n{{Fearless_class_landing_platform_dock}}\n{{Falklands War British ships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fearless (L10)}}\n[[Category:Fearless-class landing platform docks]]\n[[Category:Cold War amphibious warfare vessels of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Belfast]]\n[[Category:Falklands War naval ships of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1963 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Harland and Wolff]]\n\n[[it:HMS Fearless]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Royal Navy ship that served from 1965 until 2002}}\n{{other ships|HMS Fearless}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=HMS Fearless (L10) off North Carolina 1996.JPEG\n|Ship caption=HMS ''Fearless'' off North Carolina, 9 May 1996\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United Kingdom\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|UK|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Fearless''\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=Harland and Wolff, Belfast\n|Ship laid down= 25 July 1962\n|Ship launched=19 December 1963\n|Ship sponsor=Lady Hull, wife of [[Richard Hull|Field Marshal Sir Richard Hull]]\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned= 25 November 1965\n|Ship decommissioned= 18 March 2002\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship identification=*[[Pennant number|Pennant]] L10\n*{{IMO Number|4907177}}\n|Ship fate=Scrapped [[Ghent]] harbour (BE) 2008\n|Ship motto=*''Explicit Nomen''\n*(\"The name says it all\")\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Fearless|landing platform dock}}\n|Ship displacement=12,120 tons (full load)\n|Ship length= {{convert|520|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|80|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught={{convert|21|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship propulsion=2 \u00d7 [[English Electric]] 2 shaft geared [[steam turbine]]s. {{convert|22000|shp|abbr=on}} total\n|Ship speed={{convert|21|kn|km/h}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship capacity=\t\n|Ship complement= 580\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*2 \u00d7 [[BMARC]] GAM B01 20&nbsp;mm. single mounts\n*2 \u00d7 [[Phalanx CIWS]]\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship aircraft=Landing platform for up to 5 [[Westland Sea King|Sea King]] helicopters.\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''HMS ''Fearless'' (L10)''' was a [[Royal Navy]] amphibious assault ship that served from 1965 until 2002. One of two {{sclass-|Fearless|landing platform dock}}s, she was based in [[HMNB Portsmouth|HMNB ''Portsmouth'']] and saw service around the world over her 37-year life. She was the last steam-powered surface ship in the Royal Navy.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080726093933/http://www.btinternet.com/~warship/Today/intrepid.htm]</ref>\n\n==Role==\n\n{{main| Fearless-class landing platform dock}}\n\nThe landing platform docks (LPD) supported a [[Royal Marines]] amphibious assault force and provided a platform for the Headquarters capability prior to, and during, the assault phase. The Royal Marines served aboard as the 4th Assault Squadron. The Squadron included crew for the four [[Landing Craft Utility|LCU]]s, four [[Landing craft of the Royal Marines#LCVP Mk2|LCVP]]s and the Beach Party, which was equipped with a [[Land Rover]], a Bedford 4-ton truck, two tractor units\u2014one a track layer, the other equipped with a bucket\u2014and a Centurion [[BARV]]. The squadron also had duties aboard, (ensuring equipment and troops got to shore as they were needed), radio operators and administration.\n\n==Service==\n''Fearless'' was the first purpose-built LPD used by the Royal Navy. Built in [[Belfast]] at the [[Harland and Wolff]] yard, she was launched in 1963 before undergoing trials and commissioning in 1965.\n\nFollowing commissioning, her first operational tasking was acting as a command platform for British Counter-Terrorism operations in [[Colony of Aden|Aden]], operating [[Royal Air Force]] aircraft and the [[Irish Guards]] prior to the British withdrawal as Flag of a 25 platform task group. Following the Aden experiences, she was the venue for talks between [[Harold Wilson]] and [[Ian Smith]] in 1968, over the future of [[Rhodesia]]. The latter had unilaterally declared independence([[Unilateral Declaration of Independence (Rhodesia)|UDI]]) from Britain, owing to Britain's insistence on the removal of white minority rule.\n\nBetween 1969 and 1970 she was commanded by Captain [[John Gerard-Pearse]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mackie|first1=Colin|title=Senior Royal Navy Appointments from 1865|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Senior%20Royal%20Navy%20Appointments%201865-.pdf|website=Gulabin|publisher=Colin Mackie|accessdate=18 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1972, ''Fearless'' ferried several Centurion [[AVRE]] [[demolition vehicle]]s, derived from the [[Centurion tank]], to [[Northern Ireland]] to be deployed there as part of [[Operation Motorman]].<ref name=\"Osprey\">Osprey Publishing: Centurion Universal Tank 1943\u20132003 {{ISBN|1-84176-387-X}}{{page needed|date=October 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Fearless'' featured in the 1977 [[James Bond]] film ''[[The Spy Who Loved Me (film)|The Spy Who Loved Me]]'' as the ship that picks up Bond's escape pod. The filming took place the previous year near the island of Malta.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7024769.stm|title=HMS Fearless heads for scrapyard|work=BBC News|date=2 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:HMS Fearless, San Carlos, 1982.JPG|thumb|left|''Fearless'' in [[San Carlos, Falkland Islands|San Carlos]], during the [[Falklands War]]]]\n[[File:Sounds on board HMS Fearless.ogg|alt=Sounds on board HMS Fearless during the Falklands War.|thumb|Sounds on board HMS ''Fearless'' during the Falklands War.]]\n\n''Fearless'' was part of the [[British naval forces in the Falklands War|British naval force]] committed to [[Operation Corporate]], the 1982 [[Falklands War]]. Fitted with modern satellite communications equipment, it hosted the staff of amphibious force commander [[Commodore (Royal Navy)|Commodore]] Michael Clapp (Commodore Amphibious Warfare (COMAW)), and Commanding Officer [[3 Commando Brigade]], [[Brigadier]] [[Julian Thompson (Royal Marines officer)|Julian Thompson]] and his staff, as well as elements of the landing force. As a result of the conflict, Royal Marine Coxswain Corporal Alan White received a commendation from the Task Force Commander, Admiral Sir [[John Fieldhouse, Baron Fieldhouse|John Fieldhouse]], for his part in rescuing 41 crew from {{HMS|Antelope|F170|6}} using Foxtrot 7, one of four LCVP landing craft carried by Fearless. Foxtrot 7 is now located in the Royal Marines Museum in Portsmouth, with detailed accounts from Corporal Alan White of the missions he took part in, including the landings at San Carlos.\n\nShe was placed out of commission for three years in 1985 prior to a two-year refit at Devonport, recommissioning in 1991. During this refit, her 1940s-vintage [[Bofors 40 mm gun|40mm Bofors]] cannon and 1960s-vintage [[Sea Cat missile|Sea Cat]] anti-aircraft missile launchers were replaced by 20&nbsp;mm BMARC and [[Phalanx CIWS]] guns.\n\nFrom 1991 until 1995 she supported the sea training phase of initial officer training, undertaken at [[Britannia Royal Naval College]], as part of the Dartmouth Training Squadron.\n\nShe was due to undertake an operation in the Gulf, but that was handed to {{HMS|Ocean|L12|6}} in 2000. Her last major duty was to take part in amphibious exercises shortly before decommissioning.\n\n===Decommissioned===\n[[File:HMS Fearless (L10) 2001.jpg|thumb|HMS ''Fearless'' in the Indian Ocean, 16 November 2001.]]\n\n''Fearless'' was decommissioned in 2002 and awaited disposal in [[Fareham]] Creek, [[Hampshire]], moored alongside her [[sister ship]] {{HMS|Intrepid|L11|2}}. In October 2007, it was reported that ''Fearless'' was to be scrapped in Belgium,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7024769.stm|title=HMS Fearless heads for scrapyard|work=BBC News|date=2 October 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/EquipmentAndLogistics/FalklandsCommandShipToBeRecycled.htm|title=Falklands command ship to be recycled|work=Ministry of Defence|date=2 October 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20120817092501/http://www.mod.uk:80/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/EquipmentAndLogistics/FalklandsCommandShipToBeRecycled.htm|archive-date=17 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nfive years after the vessel was officially mothballed in Portsmouth. On 17 December 2007, ''Fearless'' was towed to [[Ghent]] in Belgium to be broken up.\n\nThis was the first warship successfully exported for recycling by any western government that fully complied with international agreements and the principles concerning environmentally sound management of waste.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.edisposals.com/docs/webversionfearless.pdf|title=Recycling of HMS Fearless|publisher=edisposals.com}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nReplacement LPDs {{HMS|Albion|L14|2}} and {{HMS|Bulwark|L15|2}} were ordered during the 1990s. They were commissioned in 2003.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.hmsfearless.co.uk/ HMS Fearless Association]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080110111551/http://www.f913westhinder.be/ Pictures of HMS Fearless being broken up]\n*[http://www.axfordsabode.org.uk/pdf-docs/fearles1.pdf HMS Fearless Book 1970\u20131972]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110207112500/http://hmsfearless-hmsintrepid.com/ HMS Fearless Operational and manning arrangements]\n{{Fearless_class_landing_platform_dock}}\n{{Falklands War British ships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fearless (L10)}}\n[[Category:Fearless-class landing platform docks]]\n[[Category:Cold War amphibious warfare vessels of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Belfast]]\n[[Category:Falklands War naval ships of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1963 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Harland and Wolff]]\n\n[[it:HMS Fearless]]\n", "name_user": "Esneoi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HMS_Fearless_(L10)"}
{"title_page": "Heinrich von Winkelried", "text_new": "[[File:Winkelriedkapelle Lory.jpg|thumb|Winkelriedskapelle (''Drachenkapelle'') dedicated to Winkelried (1828 etching). The building depicted here replaces an earlier chapel, constructed in 1893 but destroyed in 1798 in the [[French invasion of Switzerland]]. The 1672 building may in turn have built on the site of an older chapel.\n<ref>Odermatt, ''St. Magnus- oder Winkelriedskapelle auf Allweg in Nidwalden'', Geschichtsfreund d. V Orte,  1887,  p. 42.</ref>]]\n'''Heinrich von Winkelried''' (d. after 1303), known as ''Schrutan'' or ''Strut'' \"the giant\", was a medieval [[knight]] in what is now [[Central Switzerland]].\n\nAs ''Strut von Winkelried'' he became the subject of a legend which makes him the slayer of a [[dragon]].\nThe legendary ''Strut'' is placed a generation before the historical character, with a ''flouruit'' in the 1240s, and his death due to poisoning by dragon-blood recorded for 1250.\n\n==Historical character==\n{{further|Winkelried}}\n''Heinrich von Winkelried, genannt Schrutan'' is recorded in a document dated 22 April 1275.<ref>J.E.Kopp: ''Geschichtsbl\u00e4tter aus der Schweiz'', Herausgegeben von J.E. Kopp, Band 2, Seite 200, 5. Beilage III a</ref>\nAfter this date and until 1303, his name figures repeatedly as that of a witness on official documents. Nothing beyond this is known about his life.\nThe [[Winkelried]] family is well attested in 13th and 14th century, the first known member being the knight Rudolf von Winkelried, attested 1248 as a follower of [[Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor|Frederick II]]. Heinrich therefore may have been a son of Rudolf's.\nThe home castle of the Winkelried may have been at [[Ennetmoos]] near [[Stans]]. The modern municipality of Ennetmoos has chosen dragon for its coat of arms due to the legend of Schrutan.\n\nThe nickname ''Schrutan'' (also ''Strutan, Struthan, Struth'', etc.) is derived from [[German legend]], where it is given to a giant, in particular one of the guardians of the [[Rosengarten zu Worms|Rosengarten]] in [[Heldenbuch]] literature, but it also occurs as the name of a knight at [[Attila the Hun|Etzel]]'s court in the [[Nibelungenlied]] (v. 1880). Why the historical knight was given this nickname is not known, but it was not uncommon at the time for members of the knightly classes of the Holy Roman Empire to adopt pseudonyms taken from heroic fiction. \nHeinrich's sons would have been Rudolf and Walther von Winkelried, both d. c. 1325.\n[[Hermann von Liebenau]] further assumes that one ''Heinrich genannt Schrutan'' who was buried with his wife Mechthild in [[Colmar]], [[Alsace]] must be identical with the knight,<ref>Hermann von Liebenau, ''Arnold Winkelried, seine Zeit und seine That: ein historisches Bild nach neuesten Forschungen'', 1862, p. 25.</ref> who therefore would have left Switzerland at some point after 1303, but Oechsli (1898) does not accept the identity and ascribes the equality in name to coincidence.\n\n== Legend ==\n[[File:Jauslin Drache.JPG|thumb|Schrutan's fight with the dragon, by [[Karl Jauslin]] (1842&ndash;1904)]]\nThe legend is first mentioned by [[Chronicle of the Swiss Confederation|Etterlin]] (1507), without the given name ''Strut'' and without a fixed year (but placed \"before the time of [[Rudolph I of Germany|king Rudolf]]). \nIt is expanded into greater detail  in the ''[[Chronicon Helveticum]]'' by [[Aegidius Tschudi]] (d. 1570), compiled in the 16th century and first printed in 1734. Tschudi now fixes the year of the event as 1250 and specifies the identity of the hero as one ''Struth von Winkelriedt'' (which name he emphasizes is recorded in the annals of [[Stans]]), who had been knighted by emperor Frederick at the [[siege of Faenza|battle of ''Favenz'']] (1239). \nThe legend was later included by the [[Brothers Grimm]] in their collection of [[German legend]]s (''Deutsche Sagen'' 1865, no. 218).\n\nAccording to the story as reported by Tschudi, a dragon lived in a cave near [[Stans]] (the ''Drachenloch'' near the top of [[Mueterschwandenberg]]), destroying cattle and causing much damage to the people of ''Wilen'', to the point where the village had to be abandoned and came to be known as ''\u00d6dwilen'' (deserted Wilen). The people of Unterwalden made several expeditions trying to kill the dragon with crossbows, but each time the dragon saw he was at a disadvantage, he quickly retired into his cave or ran up a steep slope like a lizard, where he was unreachable. \nAt this point, Winkelried,  who had been banished from Unterwalden for manslaughter, asked whether he would be allowed back into the land if he would kill the dragon.  This was accepted, and Struth attacked the dragon single-handedly, armed with a spear, to the point of which he had attached sharp barbs.\nThe dragon seeing that the attacker was alone came from his hiding-place and attacked with open jaws, and Winkelried was able to transfix the monster with his spear, hacking at it with his sword until it died. \nGlad for his victory, Winkelried lifted his sword over his head, thanking God, and the dragon's blood dripped from his sword blade on his body, poisoning him so that he died a few days later.\n\nToponymy referring to a dragon is found in [[Ennetmoos]], where the historical  [[Winkelried]] family originated. A ''Drachenried'' (dragon's fen) and  ''Drachenloch'' (dragon's cave) are to the west of the village, and a ''Drachenkapelle'' (dragon chapel), also known as ''Winkelriedkapelle'' dedicated to Struth is south of the village, next to ''Wychried'', the probable site of the original Winkelried estate.\nThe story is probably a recontextualisation of a much older dragon myth, put into a new historical context in late medieval folklore. \nThe \"dragon\" toponymy in this place has been associated with the older dragon narrative in the [[Nibelung]] cycle in 19th-century scholarship.<ref>\nJosef Anton Henne, ''Schweizerchronik in vier B\u00fcchern: aus den Quellen untersucht und dargestellt'', p. 110.\n''Drachenkapelle'': Robert Durrer, ''Kunstdenkm\u00e4ler im Kanton Unterwalden'' (1899-1928), 255-257.\n</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* Hermann von Liebenau: ''Die Winkelriede von Stans bis auf Arnold Winkelried den Helden von Sempach. Nebst Beilagen (13 gedruckten Urkunden)'', Z\u00fcrich 1856\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winkelried, Heinrich von}}\n[[Category:Medieval knights]]\n[[Category:13th-century births]]\n[[Category:14th-century deaths]]\n[[Category:Dragonslayers]]\n[[Category:Folk saints]]\n[[Category:Swiss nobility]]\n[[Category:Swiss folklore]]\n[[Category:Winkelried family|Heinrich]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Winkelriedkapelle Lory.jpg|thumb|Winkelriedskapelle (''Drachenkapelle'') dedicated to Winkelried (1828 etching). The building depicted here replaces an earlier chapel, constructed in 1893 but destroyed in 1798 in the [[French invasion of Switzerland]]. The 1672 building may in turn have built on the site of an older chapel.\n<ref>Odermatt, ''St. Magnus- oder Winkelriedskapelle auf Allweg in Nidwalden'', Geschichtsfreund d. V Orte,  1887,  p. 42.</ref>]]\n'''Heinrich von Winkelried''' (d. after 1303), known as ''Schrutan'' or ''Strut'' \"the giant\", was a medieval [[knight]] in what is now [[Central Switzerland]].\n\nAs ''Strut von Winkelried'' he became the subject of a legend which makes him the slayer of a [[dragon]].\nThe legendary ''Strut'' is placed a generation before the historical character, with a ''flouruit'' in the 1240s, and his death due to poisoning by dragon-blood recorded for 1250.\n\n==Historical character==\n{{further|Winkelried}}\n''Heinrich von Winkelried, genannt Schrutan'' is recorded in a document dated 22 April 1275.<ref>J.E.Kopp: ''Geschichtsbl\u00e4tter aus der Schweiz'', Herausgegeben von J.E. Kopp, Band 2, Seite 200, 5. Beilage III a</ref>\nAfter this date and until 1303, his name figures repeatedly as that of a witness on official documents. Nothing beyond this is known about his life.\nThe [[Winkelried]] family is well attested in 13th and 14th century, the first known member being the knight Rudolf von Winkelried, attested 1248 as a follower of [[Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor|Frederick II]]. Heinrich therefore may have been a son of Rudolf's.\nThe home castle of the Winkelried may have been at [[Ennetmoos]] near [[Stans]]. The modern municipality of Ennetmoos has chosen dragon for its coat of arms due to the legend of Schrutan.\n\nThe nickname ''Schrutan'' (also ''Strutan, Struthan, Struth'', etc.) is derived from [[German legend]], where it is given to a giant, in particular one of the guardians of the [[Rosengarten zu Worms|Rosengarten]] in [[Heldenbuch]] literature, but it also occurs as the name of a knight at [[Attila the Hun|Etzel]]'s court in the [[Nibelungenlied]] (v. 1880). Why the historical knight was given this nickname is not known, but it was not uncommon at the time for members of the knightly classes of the Holy Roman Empire to adopt pseudonyms taken from heroic fiction. \nHeinrich's sons would have been Rudolf and Walther von Winkelried, both d. c. 1325.\n[[Hermann von Liebenau]] further assumes that one ''Heinrich genannt Schrutan'' who was buried with his wife Mechthild in [[Colmar]], [[Alsace]] must be identical with the knight,<ref>Hermann von Liebenau, ''Arnold Winkelried, seine Zeit und seine That: ein historisches Bild nach neuesten Forschungen'', 1862, p. 25.</ref> who therefore would have left Switzerland at some point after 1303, but Oechsli (1898) does not accept the identity and ascribes the equality in name to coincidence.\n\n== Legend ==\n[[File:Jauslin Drache.JPG|thumb|Schrutan's fight with the dragon,  by [[Karl Jauslin]] (1842&ndash;1904)]]\nThe legend is first mentioned by [[Chronicle of the Swiss Confederation|Etterlin]] (1507), without the given name ''Strut'' and without a fixed year (but placed \"before the time of [[Rudolph I of Germany|king Rudolf]]). \nIt is expanded into greater detail  in the ''[[Chronicon Helveticum]]'' by [[Aegidius Tschudi]] (d. 1570), compiled in the 16th century and first printed in 1734. Tschudi now fixes the year of the event as 1250 and speficies the identity of the hero as one ''Struth von Winkelriedt'' (which name he emphasizes is recorded in the annals of [[Stans]]), who had been knighted by emperor Frederick at the [[siege of Faenza|battle of ''Favenz'']] (1239). \nThe legend was later included by the [[Brothers Grimm]] in their collection of [[German legend]]s (''Deutsche Sagen'' 1865, no. 218).\n\nAccording to the story as reported by Tschudi, a dragon lived in a cave near [[Stans]] (the ''Drachenloch'' near the top of [[Mueterschwandenberg]]), destroying cattle and causing much damage to the people of ''Wilen'', to the point where the village had to be abandoned and came to be known as ''\u00d6dwilen'' (deserted Wilen). The people of Unterwalden made several expeditions trying to kill the dragon with crossbows, but each time the dragon saw he was at a disadvantage, he quickly retired into his cave or ran up a steep slope like a lizard, where he was unreachable. \nAt this point, Winkelried,  who had been banished from Unterwalden for manslaughter, asked whether he would be allowed back into the land if he would kill the dragon.  This was accepted, and Struth attacked the dragon single-handedly, armed with a spear, to the point of which he had attached sharp barbs.\nThe dragon seeing that the attacker was alone came from his hiding-place and attacked with open jaws, and Winkelried was able to transfix the monster with his spear, hacking at it with his sword until it died. \nGlad for his victory, Winkelried lifted his sword over his head, thanking God, and the dragon's blood dripped from his sword blade on his body, poisoning him so that he died a few days later.\n\nToponymy referring to a dragon is found in [[Ennetmoos]], where the historical  [[Winkelried]] family originated. A ''Drachenried'' (dragon's fen) and  ''Drachenloch'' (dragon's cave) are to the west of the village, and a ''Drachenkapelle'' (dragon chapel), also known as ''Winkelriedkapelle'' dedicated to Struth is south of the village, next to ''Wychried'', the probable site of the original Winkelried estate.\nThe story is probably a recontextualisation of a much older dragon myth, put into a new historical context in late medieval folklore. \nThe \"dragon\" toponymy in this place has been associated with the older dragon narrative in the [[Nibelung]] cycle in 19th-century scholarship.<ref>\nJosef Anton Henne, ''Schweizerchronik in vier B\u00fcchern: aus den Quellen untersucht und dargestellt'', p. 110.\n''Drachenkapelle'': Robert Durrer, ''Kunstdenkm\u00e4ler im Kanton Unterwalden'' (1899-1928), 255-257.\n</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* Hermann von Liebenau: ''Die Winkelriede von Stans bis auf Arnold Winkelried den Helden von Sempach. Nebst Beilagen (13 gedruckten Urkunden)'', Z\u00fcrich 1856\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winkelried, Heinrich von}}\n[[Category:Medieval knights]]\n[[Category:13th-century births]]\n[[Category:14th-century deaths]]\n[[Category:Dragonslayers]]\n[[Category:Folk saints]]\n[[Category:Swiss nobility]]\n[[Category:Swiss folklore]]\n[[Category:Winkelried family|Heinrich]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: speficies \u2192 specifies", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heinrich_von_Winkelried"}
{"title_page": "Laurie Patton (Australian executive)", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Laurie Patton (Australian executive)|timestamp=20200409052303|year=2020|month=April|day=9|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Laurie Patton (Australian executive)|date=9 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Autobiography|date=April 2020}}\n{{Primary sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{Unreliable sources|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Laurie Patton.jpeg|thumb|Laurie Patton]] -->[[File:Laurie Patton.jpg|thumb|Laurie Patton]]\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n'''Laurie Patton''' is an [[Australia]]n public interest advocacy and communications practitioner, social commentator,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themandarin.com.au/130213-a-virtual-solution-to-21st-century-government/|title=A virtual solution to 21st century government|date=8 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408030825/https://www.themandarin.com.au/130213-a-virtual-solution-to-21st-century-government/|archive-date=8 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themandarin.com.au/120312-op-ed-we-wouldnt-need-inquiries-if-public-administration-wasnt-so-broken/|title=Op-ed: we wouldn't need inquiries if public administration wasn't so broken|date=13 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Laurie |first1=Patton |title=The Case For Mandating Governance Training For NFP Boards {{!}} PBA |url=https://probonoaustralia.com.au/news/2017/06/case-mandating-governance-training-nfp-boards/ |website=Pro Bono Australia |accessdate=9 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209040050/https://probonoaustralia.com.au/news/2017/06/case-mandating-governance-training-nfp-boards/ |archive-date=9 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crikey.com.au/2018/04/03/no-balls-how-cricket-australia-lost-the-media-game/|title=No balls: how Cricket Australia lost the media game|date=3 April 2018|website=Crikey|access-date=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180513054659/https://www.crikey.com.au/2018/04/03/no-balls-how-cricket-australia-lost-the-media-game/|archive-date=13 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-sports-rorts-shows-need-for-public-sector-re-think/|title=LAURIE PATTON. Sports rorts shows need for public sector re-think | author = [[John Menadue]] |date=19 February 2020|access-date=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221075652/https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-sports-rorts-shows-need-for-public-sector-re-think/|archive-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and a former journalist and media executive. He is currently Vice-President of the [[Telecommunications Society of Australia]] (TelSoc).<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.itwire.com/business-technology/australia-%E2%80%9Cfalling-behind%E2%80%9D-apac-in-developing-technologies,-says-telsoc-chief.html |title=Australia 'falling behind' APAC in developing technologies, says Telsoc chief | work = [[iTWire]] | author = Peter Dinham |date=2019-12-03 |accessdate=2020-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=About Telsoc {{!}} Telsoc |url=https://telsoc.org/about |website=telsoc.org |publisher=Telsoc |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thesaturdaypaper.com.au/2020/04/04/nbn-under-pressure/15859188009638|title=NBN under pressure|first=Paddy|last=Manning|date=4 April 2020|website=The Saturday Paper|access-date=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407080710/https://www.thesaturdaypaper.com.au/2020/04/04/nbn-under-pressure/15859188009638|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-overexposed-lets-hear-from-someone-else/|title=LAURIE PATTON. Overexposed \u2013 let's hear from someone else! | author = [[John Menadue]] | date=28 January 2020|access-date=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128234055/https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-overexposed-lets-hear-from-someone-else/|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nNow active in the [[non-profit]] sector Patton is a former CEO / Executive Director of [[Internet Australia]],<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.internet.org.au/team/26-about-us/62-roll-of-honour | title=Roll of Honour - Directors and Staff - Internet Australia - A Chapter of the Internet Society | access-date=24 April 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424135758/https://www.internet.org.au/team/26-about-us/62-roll-of-honour | archive-date=24 April 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.itnews.com.au/news/tv-exec-named-first-ceo-of-isoc-au-398187|title=TV exec named first CEO of ISOC-AU |access-date=27 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127110346/https://www.itnews.com.au/news/tv-exec-named-first-ceo-of-isoc-au-398187| work = [[itnews]] | author = Andrew Colley | archive-date=27 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> the peak body representing the interests of Internet users and a chapter of the global [[Internet Society]], where he initiated an ongoing campaign for #BetterBroadband.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvblackbox.com.au/page/2019/5/7/multi-technology-mess-why-the-film-and-tv-industry-should-be-fighting-for-betterbroadband|title=Multi-technology mess. Why the film and TV industry should be fighting for #BetterBroadband|website=Australian Television News - TV Blackbox|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329074401/https://tvblackbox.com.au/page/2019/5/7/multi-technology-mess-why-the-film-and-tv-industry-should-be-fighting-for-betterbroadband|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/life/tech/2020/03/11/hfc-outage-nbn-tpg/|title='Not up to operational standards': NBN HFC outages soar, TPG reveals|date=11 March 2020|website=The New Daily|access-date=29 March 2020 | author = Isabelle Lane | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329074401/https://thenewdaily.com.au/life/tech/2020/03/11/hfc-outage-nbn-tpg/|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itwire.com/strategy/patton-calls-for-govt-to-fund-nbn-co-to-employ-those-retrenched-due-to-covit-19-crisis.html|title=iTWire - Telsoc VP calls for govt to fund NBN Co to employ those retrenched due to COVID-19 crisis|first=Peter|last=Dinham|website=www.itwire.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ia.acs.org.au/article/2020/is-now-the-time-to-fix-the-nbn-.html|title=Is now the time to fix the NBN?|website=Information Age}}</ref>\n\nShortly after joining Internet Australia Patton told a parliamentary inquiry the drafting of the controversial Date Retention Act ([[Telecommunications (Interception and Access) Amendment (Data Retention) Act 2015]]) was \"a monumental stuff-up\" and \u201cfundamentally flawed\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/jan/12/data-retention-law-a-monumental-stuff-up-says-internet-users-group|title=Data retention law a 'monumental stuff-up', says internet users group|first=Elle|last=Hunt|date=11 January 2017|via=www.theguardian.com|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304022533/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/jan/12/data-retention-law-a-monumental-stuff-up-says-internet-users-group|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.internet.org.au/news/136-17-september-2015-news-release-internet-australia-says-fundamentally-flawed-data-retention-act-needs-urgent-review|title=17 September 2015 - NEWS RELEASE: Internet Australia says \"fundamentally flawed\" Data Retention Act needs urgent review - Internet Australia - A Chapter of the Internet Society|website=www.internet.org.au|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329074403/https://www.internet.org.au/news/136-17-september-2015-news-release-internet-australia-says-fundamentally-flawed-data-retention-act-needs-urgent-review|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://technologydecisions.com.au/content/it-management/article/isps-unhappy-at-data-retention-funding-split-1162633669|title=ISPs unhappy at data retention funding split|website=technologydecisions.com.au|access-date=9 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329074403/https://www.technologydecisions.com.au/content/it-management/article/isps-unhappy-at-data-retention-funding-split-1162633669|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-the-data-retention-act-how-not-to-introduce-complex-legislation/|title=LAURIE PATTON. The Data Retention Act. How not to introduce complex legislation.|date=10 February 2020|access-date=29 March 2020 | author = [[John Menadue]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329074402/https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-the-data-retention-act-how-not-to-introduce-complex-legislation/|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2016/dec/07/data-retention-isps-australia-counter-terrorism-laws-advocates|title=Data retention black hole: no one knows how many ISPs Australia has, say experts|first=Elle|last=Hunt|date=6 December 2016|via=www.theguardian.com|access-date=4 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704062234/https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2016/dec/07/data-retention-isps-australia-counter-terrorism-laws-advocates|archive-date=4 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He subsequently commented on matters such as digital literacy, broadband policy,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologydecisions.com.au/content/networking/news/nbn-connections-grow-to-6-6m-in-dec-quarter-833948398|title=nbn connections grow to 6.6m in Dec quarter|website=www.technologydecisions.com.au|access-date=29 March 2020 | author = Dylan Bushell-Embling |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304022533/https://www.technologydecisions.com.au/content/networking/news/nbn-connections-grow-to-6-6m-in-dec-quarter-833948398|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themandarin.com.au/125569-opinion-sports-rorts-shows-need-for-public-sector-re-think/|title=Opinion: Sports rorts shows need for public sector re-think|date=19 February 2020|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221125718/https://www.themandarin.com.au/125569-opinion-sports-rorts-shows-need-for-public-sector-re-think/|archive-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>https://www.technologydecisions.com.au/content/networking/article/opinion-oh-dear-what-can-the-matter-be--883223376 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310134216/https://www.technologydecisions.com.au/content/networking/article/opinion-oh-dear-what-can-the-matter-be--883223376 |date=10 March 2020 }}]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themandarin.com.au/127522-telstra-puts-a-bell-on-the-broadband-cat-and-spays-nbn-co/|title=Telstra puts a bell on the broadband cat and spays NBN Co|date=16 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329170034/https://www.themandarin.com.au/127522-telstra-puts-a-bell-on-the-broadband-cat-and-spays-nbn-co/|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-23/how-project-thunder-could-have-changed-australian-television/7050546|title=Project Thunder: The Aussie rival to Netflix that never was|first=Corey|last=Hague|date=23 December 2015|website=ABC News|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426171403/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-23/how-project-thunder-could-have-changed-australian-television/7050546|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPatton is a former executive at the [[Seven Network]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://tvblackbox.com.au/page/2019/8/22/opinion-james-warburton-needs-to-stamp-out-the-arrogance-at-seven|title=OPINION &#124; James Warburton needs to stamp out the arrogance at SEVEN|website=Australian Television News - TV Blackbox|access-date=29 March 2020 | author = Robert McKnight |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209040051/https://tvblackbox.com.au/page/2019/8/22/opinion-james-warburton-needs-to-stamp-out-the-arrogance-at-seven|archive-date=9 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvblackbox.com.au/authors/tag/Laurie+Patton|title=Laurie Patton \u2014 Authors|website=Australian Television News - TV Blackbox|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329074402/https://tvblackbox.com.au/authors/tag/Laurie%2BPatton|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.crikey.com.au/2017/02/20/laurie-patton-7-30-got-it-wrong-on-today-tonight-and-kennett/|title=Laurie Patton: 7.30 got it wrong on Today Tonight and Kennett -- and refuses to correct the record|date=20 February 2017|website=Crikey|access-date=29 March 2020 | author = Jill Singer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329074400/https://www.crikey.com.au/2017/02/20/laurie-patton-7-30-got-it-wrong-on-today-tonight-and-kennett/|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/> He created the [[World Movies]] Pay-TV channel<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/> and was founding CEO of community station TVS ([[Television Sydney]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.if.com.au/tvs-laurie-patton-signs-off/|title=TVS' Laurie Patton signs off|date=28 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nPatton has held for-profit and non-profit board roles, including at the [[National Heart Foundation of Australia]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/images/uploads/publications/HFN0865_HF_AnnualReview_15_170516_F_LLR.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190311061231/https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/images/uploads/publications/HFN0865_HF_AnnualReview_15_170516_F_LLR.pdf |archive-date=11 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the NSW Film & Television Office (now [[Screen NSW]]).<ref>https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/images/uploads/main/About_us/NSW-Annual-Report.pd</ref> As deputy chair of the FTO he initiated and led the first official Australian delegation to the Shanghai International Film Festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/china-assesses-co-production-potential-with-south-africa-australia/4011383.article|title=China assesses co-production potential with South Africa, Australia|first=Staff|last=reporters2002-11-27T04:05:00+00:00|website=Screen|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304022528/https://www.screendaily.com/china-assesses-co-production-potential-with-south-africa-australia/4011383.article|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live | quote = While Patton and FTO chief executive Jane Smith are trying to create a channel for distributors of Australia films - Chinese films screen in Australia commercially, in festivals, and on television - they are as interested in cultural exchange, including the development of co-productions.}}</ref><ref name=nswAnnual2002/> He was a member of an expert panel for a review of the Indigenous broadcasting and media sector for the Australian Government.<ref name=firstNationsMedia/>\n\nSince joining TelSoc Patton has continued to campaign for repair of the [[National Broadband Network]] (NBN)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/life/tech/2020/02/12/nbn-budget-deadline-2020/|title=NBN won't be finished on time or within budget, telco experts say|date=11 February 2020|website=The New Daily|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401220847/https://thenewdaily.com.au/life/tech/2020/02/12/nbn-budget-deadline-2020/|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theluckygeneral.biz/2020/03/31/the-minister-and-the-elephant-a-broadband-tale/#more-3310,%20http://technologydecisions.com.au/content/networking/article/the-minister-and-the-elephant-a-broadband-tale-1173218937|title=The Minister and the elephant: a broadband tale|website=theluckygeneral.biz|access-date=9 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409075200/https://theluckygeneral.biz/2020/03/31/the-minister-and-the-elephant-a-broadband-tale/#more-3310,%20http://technologydecisions.com.au/content/networking/article/the-minister-and-the-elephant-a-broadband-tale-1173218937|archive-date=9 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and has advocated the allocation of government [[Coronavirus]] stimulous funding for the employment of retrenched workers to be deployed to upgrade the NBN.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themandarin.com.au/128618-an-opportunity-for-the-prime-ministers-national-covid-19-coordination-commission-to-prove-its-mettle/|title=An opportunity for the Prime Minister's National COVID-19 Coordination Commission to prove its mettle|date=25 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329074401/https://www.themandarin.com.au/128618-an-opportunity-for-the-prime-ministers-national-covid-19-coordination-commission-to-prove-its-mettle/|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet | user= theprojecttv | number = 1241631118920765441 |  url=https://twitter.com/theprojecttv/status/1241631118920765441?s=21|title=What does the federal government need to do in order to fix the NBN? We asked an expert and this is actually a really good idea!pic.twitter.com/anNrAzaSSX | author = The Project TV | author-link= The Project (Australian TV program) |date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crikey.com.au/2020/04/06/nbn-digital-divide-australia/|title=It's never been more important to close the digital divide|date=6 April 2020|website=Crikey|access-date=6 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406190457/https://www.crikey.com.au/2020/04/06/nbn-digital-divide-australia/|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em|refs=\n<ref name=firstNationsMedia>\n{{cite news     \n| url         = https://firstnationsmedia.org.au/sites/default/files/files/Stevens-Review-2010-review-broadcasting-investment.pdf\n| title       = Review of Australian Government Investment in the Indigenous Broadcasting and Media Sector\n| access-date = 27 November 2018 \n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181127110509/https://firstnationsmedia.org.au/sites/default/files/files/Stevens-Review-2010-review-broadcasting-investment.pdf \n| archive-date= 27 November 2018 \n| url-status  = live \n| work        = [[First Nations Media]]\n| date        = 2010\n| page        = \n\n| quote       =  The Deputy Chair, Laurie Patton, led a delegation of Australian filmmakers to the Shanghai International Film Festival and TV Market, on behalf of the Premier.\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=nswAnnual2002>\n{{cite news     \n| url         = https://media.opengov.nsw.gov.au/pairtree_root/16/11/8d/de/d2/e0/34/57/9a/08/05/94/a7/19/ab/d3/obj/document.pdf                \n| title       = NEW SOUTH WALES FILM AND TELEVISION OFFICE ANNUAL REPORT 2001/2002\n| work        = \n| date        = 2002\n| page        = \n| archive-date=4 March 2020 \n| url-status  = live \n| archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20200304022531/https://media.opengov.nsw.gov.au/pairtree_root/16/11/8d/de/d2/e0/34/57/9a/08/05/94/a7/19/ab/d3/obj/document.pdf \n| accessdate  = 2020-04-11\n| quote       =  The Deputy Chair, Laurie Patton, led a delegation of Australian filmmakers to the Shanghai International Film Festival and TV Market, on behalf of the Premier.\n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*''[https://theluckygeneral.biz The Lucky General]'', Laurie Patton's blog\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patton, Laurie}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian chief executives]]\n[[Category:Australian bloggers]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Laurie Patton (Australian executive)|timestamp=20200409052303|year=2020|month=April|day=9|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Laurie Patton (Australian executive)|date=9 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Autobiography|date=April 2020}}\n{{Primary sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{Unreliable sources|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Laurie Patton.jpeg|thumb|Laurie Patton]] -->[[File:Laurie Patton.jpg|thumb|Laurie Patton]]\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n'''Laurie Patton''' is an [[Australia]]n public interest advocacy and communications practitioner, social commentator,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themandarin.com.au/130213-a-virtual-solution-to-21st-century-government/|title=A virtual solution to 21st century government|date=8 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408030825/https://www.themandarin.com.au/130213-a-virtual-solution-to-21st-century-government/|archive-date=8 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themandarin.com.au/120312-op-ed-we-wouldnt-need-inquiries-if-public-administration-wasnt-so-broken/|title=Op-ed: we wouldn't need inquiries if public administration wasn't so broken|date=13 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Laurie |first1=Patton |title=The Case For Mandating Governance Training For NFP Boards {{!}} PBA |url=https://probonoaustralia.com.au/news/2017/06/case-mandating-governance-training-nfp-boards/ |website=Pro Bono Australia |accessdate=9 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209040050/https://probonoaustralia.com.au/news/2017/06/case-mandating-governance-training-nfp-boards/ |archive-date=9 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crikey.com.au/2018/04/03/no-balls-how-cricket-australia-lost-the-media-game/|title=No balls: how Cricket Australia lost the media game|date=3 April 2018|website=Crikey|access-date=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180513054659/https://www.crikey.com.au/2018/04/03/no-balls-how-cricket-australia-lost-the-media-game/|archive-date=13 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-sports-rorts-shows-need-for-public-sector-re-think/|title=LAURIE PATTON. Sports rorts shows need for public sector re-think | author = [[John Menadue]] |date=19 February 2020|access-date=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221075652/https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-sports-rorts-shows-need-for-public-sector-re-think/|archive-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and a former journalist and media executive. He is currently Vice-President of the [[Telecommunications Society of Australia]] (TelSoc).<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.itwire.com/business-technology/australia-%E2%80%9Cfalling-behind%E2%80%9D-apac-in-developing-technologies,-says-telsoc-chief.html |title=Australia 'falling behind' APAC in developing technologies, says Telsoc chief | work = [[iTWire]] | author = Peter Dinham |date=2019-12-03 |accessdate=2020-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=About Telsoc {{!}} Telsoc |url=https://telsoc.org/about |website=telsoc.org |publisher=Telsoc |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thesaturdaypaper.com.au/2020/04/04/nbn-under-pressure/15859188009638|title=NBN under pressure|first=Paddy|last=Manning|date=4 April 2020|website=The Saturday Paper|access-date=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407080710/https://www.thesaturdaypaper.com.au/2020/04/04/nbn-under-pressure/15859188009638|archive-date=7 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-overexposed-lets-hear-from-someone-else/|title=LAURIE PATTON. Overexposed \u2013 let's hear from someone else! | author = [[John Menadue]] | date=28 January 2020|access-date=5 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128234055/https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-overexposed-lets-hear-from-someone-else/|archive-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nNow active in the [[non-profit]] sector Patton is a former CEO / Executive Director of [[Internet Australia]],<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.internet.org.au/team/26-about-us/62-roll-of-honour | title=Roll of Honour - Directors and Staff - Internet Australia - A Chapter of the Internet Society | access-date=24 April 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424135758/https://www.internet.org.au/team/26-about-us/62-roll-of-honour | archive-date=24 April 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.itnews.com.au/news/tv-exec-named-first-ceo-of-isoc-au-398187|title=TV exec named first CEO of ISOC-AU |access-date=27 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127110346/https://www.itnews.com.au/news/tv-exec-named-first-ceo-of-isoc-au-398187| work = [[itnews]] | author = Andrew Colley | archive-date=27 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> the peak body representing the interests of Internet users and a chapter of the global [[Internet Society]], where he initiated an ongoing campaign for #BetterBroadband.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvblackbox.com.au/page/2019/5/7/multi-technology-mess-why-the-film-and-tv-industry-should-be-fighting-for-betterbroadband|title=Multi-technology mess. Why the film and TV industry should be fighting for #BetterBroadband|website=Australian Television News - TV Blackbox|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329074401/https://tvblackbox.com.au/page/2019/5/7/multi-technology-mess-why-the-film-and-tv-industry-should-be-fighting-for-betterbroadband|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/life/tech/2020/03/11/hfc-outage-nbn-tpg/|title='Not up to operational standards': NBN HFC outages soar, TPG reveals|date=11 March 2020|website=The New Daily|access-date=29 March 2020 | author = Isabelle Lane | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329074401/https://thenewdaily.com.au/life/tech/2020/03/11/hfc-outage-nbn-tpg/|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itwire.com/strategy/patton-calls-for-govt-to-fund-nbn-co-to-employ-those-retrenched-due-to-covit-19-crisis.html|title=iTWire - Telsoc VP calls for govt to fund NBN Co to employ those retrenched due to COVID-19 crisis|first=Peter|last=Dinham|website=www.itwire.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ia.acs.org.au/article/2020/is-now-the-time-to-fix-the-nbn-.html|title=Is now the time to fix the NBN?|website=Information Age}}</ref>\n\nShortly after joining Internet Australia Patton told a parliamentary inquiry the drafting of the controversial Date Retention Act ([[Telecommunications (Interception and Access) Amendment (Data Retention) Act 2015]]) was \"a monumental stuff-up\" and \u201cfundamentally flawed\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/jan/12/data-retention-law-a-monumental-stuff-up-says-internet-users-group|title=Data retention law a 'monumental stuff-up', says internet users group|first=Elle|last=Hunt|date=11 January 2017|via=www.theguardian.com|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304022533/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/jan/12/data-retention-law-a-monumental-stuff-up-says-internet-users-group|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.internet.org.au/news/136-17-september-2015-news-release-internet-australia-says-fundamentally-flawed-data-retention-act-needs-urgent-review|title=17 September 2015 - NEWS RELEASE: Internet Australia says \"fundamentally flawed\" Data Retention Act needs urgent review - Internet Australia - A Chapter of the Internet Society|website=www.internet.org.au|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329074403/https://www.internet.org.au/news/136-17-september-2015-news-release-internet-australia-says-fundamentally-flawed-data-retention-act-needs-urgent-review|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://technologydecisions.com.au/content/it-management/article/isps-unhappy-at-data-retention-funding-split-1162633669|title=ISPs unhappy at data retention funding split|website=technologydecisions.com.au|access-date=9 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329074403/https://www.technologydecisions.com.au/content/it-management/article/isps-unhappy-at-data-retention-funding-split-1162633669|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-the-data-retention-act-how-not-to-introduce-complex-legislation/|title=LAURIE PATTON. The Data Retention Act. How not to introduce complex legislation.|date=10 February 2020|access-date=29 March 2020 | author = [[John Menadue]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329074402/https://johnmenadue.com/laurie-patton-the-data-retention-act-how-not-to-introduce-complex-legislation/|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2016/dec/07/data-retention-isps-australia-counter-terrorism-laws-advocates|title=Data retention black hole: no one knows how many ISPs Australia has, say experts|first=Elle|last=Hunt|date=6 December 2016|via=www.theguardian.com|access-date=4 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704062234/https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2016/dec/07/data-retention-isps-australia-counter-terrorism-laws-advocates|archive-date=4 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He subsequently commented on matters such as digital literacy, broadband policy,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologydecisions.com.au/content/networking/news/nbn-connections-grow-to-6-6m-in-dec-quarter-833948398|title=nbn connections grow to 6.6m in Dec quarter|website=www.technologydecisions.com.au|access-date=29 March 2020 | author = Dylan Bushell-Embling |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304022533/https://www.technologydecisions.com.au/content/networking/news/nbn-connections-grow-to-6-6m-in-dec-quarter-833948398|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themandarin.com.au/125569-opinion-sports-rorts-shows-need-for-public-sector-re-think/|title=Opinion: Sports rorts shows need for public sector re-think|date=19 February 2020|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221125718/https://www.themandarin.com.au/125569-opinion-sports-rorts-shows-need-for-public-sector-re-think/|archive-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>https://www.technologydecisions.com.au/content/networking/article/opinion-oh-dear-what-can-the-matter-be--883223376 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310134216/https://www.technologydecisions.com.au/content/networking/article/opinion-oh-dear-what-can-the-matter-be--883223376 |date=10 March 2020 }}]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themandarin.com.au/127522-telstra-puts-a-bell-on-the-broadband-cat-and-spays-nbn-co/|title=Telstra puts a bell on the broadband cat and spays NBN Co|date=16 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329170034/https://www.themandarin.com.au/127522-telstra-puts-a-bell-on-the-broadband-cat-and-spays-nbn-co/|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-23/how-project-thunder-could-have-changed-australian-television/7050546|title=Project Thunder: The Aussie rival to Netflix that never was|first=Corey|last=Hague|date=23 December 2015|website=ABC News|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426171403/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-23/how-project-thunder-could-have-changed-australian-television/7050546|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPatton is a former executive at the [[Seven Network]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://tvblackbox.com.au/page/2019/8/22/opinion-james-warburton-needs-to-stamp-out-the-arrogance-at-seven|title=OPINION &#124; James Warburton needs to stamp out the arrogance at SEVEN|website=Australian Television News - TV Blackbox|access-date=29 March 2020 | author = Robert McKnight |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209040051/https://tvblackbox.com.au/page/2019/8/22/opinion-james-warburton-needs-to-stamp-out-the-arrogance-at-seven|archive-date=9 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvblackbox.com.au/authors/tag/Laurie+Patton|title=Laurie Patton \u2014 Authors|website=Australian Television News - TV Blackbox|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329074402/https://tvblackbox.com.au/authors/tag/Laurie%2BPatton|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.crikey.com.au/2017/02/20/laurie-patton-7-30-got-it-wrong-on-today-tonight-and-kennett/|title=Laurie Patton: 7.30 got it wrong on Today Tonight and Kennett -- and refuses to correct the record|date=20 February 2017|website=Crikey|access-date=29 March 2020 | author = Jill Singer |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329074400/https://www.crikey.com.au/2017/02/20/laurie-patton-7-30-got-it-wrong-on-today-tonight-and-kennett/|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/> He created the [[World Movies]] Pay-TV channel<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/> and was founding CEO of community station TVS ([[Television Sydney]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.if.com.au/tvs-laurie-patton-signs-off/|title=TVS' Laurie Patton signs off|date=28 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nPatton has held for-profit and non-profit board roles, including at the [[National Heart Foundation of Australia]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/images/uploads/publications/HFN0865_HF_AnnualReview_15_170516_F_LLR.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190311061231/https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/images/uploads/publications/HFN0865_HF_AnnualReview_15_170516_F_LLR.pdf |archive-date=11 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the NSW Film & Television Office (now [[Screen NSW]]).<ref>https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/images/uploads/main/About_us/NSW-Annual-Report.pd</ref> As deputy chair of the FTO he initiated and led the first official Australian delegation to the Shanghai International Film Festival.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/china-assesses-co-production-potential-with-south-africa-australia/4011383.article|title=China assesses co-production potential with South Africa, Australia|first=Staff|last=reporters2002-11-27T04:05:00+00:00|website=Screen|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304022528/https://www.screendaily.com/china-assesses-co-production-potential-with-south-africa-australia/4011383.article|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live | quote = While Patton and FTO chief executive Jane Smith are trying to create a channel for distributors of Australia films - Chinese films screen in Australia commercially, in festivals, and on television - they are as interested in cultural exchange, including the development of co-productions.}}</ref><ref name=nswAnnual2002/> He was a member of an expert panel for a review of the Indigenous broadcasting and media sector for the Australian Government.<ref name=firstNationsMedia/>\n\nSince joining TelSoc Patton has continued to campaign for repair of the [[National Broadband Network]] (NBN)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/life/tech/2020/02/12/nbn-budget-deadline-2020/|title=NBN won't be finished on time or within budget, telco experts say|date=11 February 2020|website=The New Daily|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401220847/https://thenewdaily.com.au/life/tech/2020/02/12/nbn-budget-deadline-2020/|archive-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theluckygeneral.biz/2020/03/31/the-minister-and-the-elephant-a-broadband-tale/#more-3310,%20http://technologydecisions.com.au/content/networking/article/the-minister-and-the-elephant-a-broadband-tale-1173218937|title=The Minister and the elephant: a broadband tale|website=theluckygeneral.biz|access-date=9 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409075200/https://theluckygeneral.biz/2020/03/31/the-minister-and-the-elephant-a-broadband-tale/#more-3310,%20http://technologydecisions.com.au/content/networking/article/the-minister-and-the-elephant-a-broadband-tale-1173218937|archive-date=9 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and has advocated the allocation of government [[Coronavirus]] stimulous funding for the employment of retrenched workers to be deployed to upgrade the NBN.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themandarin.com.au/128618-an-opportunity-for-the-prime-ministers-national-covid-19-coordination-commission-to-prove-its-mettle/|title=An opportunity for the Prime Minister's National COVID-19 Coordination Commission to prove its mettle|date=25 March 2020|access-date=29 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329074401/https://www.themandarin.com.au/128618-an-opportunity-for-the-prime-ministers-national-covid-19-coordination-commission-to-prove-its-mettle/|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet | user= theprojecttv | number = 1241631118920765441 |  url=https://twitter.com/theprojecttv/status/1241631118920765441?s=21|title=What does the federal government need to do in order to fix the NBN? We asked an expert and this is actually a really good idea!pic.twitter.com/anNrAzaSSX | author = The Project TV | author-link= The Project (Australian TV program) |date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crikey.com.au/2020/04/06/nbn-digital-divide-australia/|title=It's never been more important to close the digital divide|date=6 April 2020|website=Crikey|access-date=6 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406190457/https://www.crikey.com.au/2020/04/06/nbn-digital-divide-australia/|archive-date=6 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em|refs=\n<ref name=firstNationsMedia>\n{{cite news     \n| url         = https://firstnationsmedia.org.au/sites/default/files/files/Stevens-Review-2010-review-broadcasting-investment.pdf\n| title       = Review of Australian Government Investment in the Indigenous Broadcasting and Media Sector\n|a ccess-date = 27 November 2018 \n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181127110509/https://firstnationsmedia.org.au/sites/default/files/files/Stevens-Review-2010-review-broadcasting-investment.pdf \n| archive-date= 27 November 2018 \n| url-status  = live \n| work        = [[First Nations Media]]\n| date        = 2010\n| page        = \n\n| quote       =  The Deputy Chair, Laurie Patton, led a delegation of Australian filmmakers to the Shanghai International Film Festival and TV Market, on behalf of the Premier.\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=nswAnnual2002>\n{{cite news     \n| url         = https://media.opengov.nsw.gov.au/pairtree_root/16/11/8d/de/d2/e0/34/57/9a/08/05/94/a7/19/ab/d3/obj/document.pdf                \n| title       = NEW SOUTH WALES FILM AND TELEVISION OFFICE ANNUAL REPORT 2001/2002\n| work        = \n| date        = 2002\n| page        = \n| archive-date=4 March 2020 \n| url-status  = live \n| archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20200304022531/https://media.opengov.nsw.gov.au/pairtree_root/16/11/8d/de/d2/e0/34/57/9a/08/05/94/a7/19/ab/d3/obj/document.pdf \n| accessdate  = 2020-04-11\n| quote       =  The Deputy Chair, Laurie Patton, led a delegation of Australian filmmakers to the Shanghai International Film Festival and TV Market, on behalf of the Premier.\n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*''[https://theluckygeneral.biz The Lucky General]'', Laurie Patton's blog\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patton, Laurie}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian chief executives]]\n[[Category:Australian bloggers]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed cite error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laurie_Patton_(Australian_executive)"}
{"title_page": "Jatav", "text_new": "{{short description|Caste of India}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{use Indian English|date=July 2017}}\n\n'''Jatav''' are the sub-caste, who are classified as a [[Scheduled Caste]] under modern India's [[Reservation in India|system of positive discrimination]].<ref name=\"Chandel 1990 51\"/>\n\nAccording to the [[2011 Census of India]], the Jatav community of [[Uttar Pradesh]] comprised 54% of that state's total 22,496,047 Scheduled Caste population.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/Jatavs-on-top-of-SC-population-in-UP/articleshow/47931787.cms |title=Jatavs on top of SC population in UP |date=4 July 2015 |work=The Times of India}}</ref> In [[Rajasthan]], the Jatavs form 24% of the Scheduled Caste population.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Scheduled castes in Rajasthan |first=Umesh Kishor |last=Jonwal |journal=CASIR |volume=4 |issue=2 |pages=578-586}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nSome authors have disputed being jatav as lower cast. In the 1920s, Jatavs claimed to be survivors of the ancient war between [[Parashuram]], the legend of the [[Brahmin]]s, and [[Kshatriya]]s, forced into hiding. Their proof of ancestry is a series of correspondences or status similarities between Jatav and other Kshatriya clans. According to Owen Lynch, \"These included identical gotras, and such Kshatriya-like ceremonies as shooting a cannon at weddings and the use of the bow and arrow at the birth [[sa\u1e43sk\u0101ra]]\".<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=_g-_r-9Oa_sC&lpg=PP1&dq=Structure%20and%20Change%20in%20Indian%20Society&pg=PA217 |title=Structure and Change in Indian Society |first=Owen M. |last=Lynch |chapter=The Politics of Untouchability: A Case From Agra |editor1-first=Milton B. |editor1-last=Singer |editor2-first=Bernard S. |editor2-last=Cohn |page=217 |publisher=Transaction Publishers |year=1970 |isbn= 978-0-20236-933-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Reconsidering Untouchability: Chamars and Dalit history in North India |first=Ramnarayan S. |last=Rawat |page=127 |publisher=Indiana University Press |year=2011 |isbn=978-0-253-22262-6 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to M. P. S. Chandel {{quote|Jatavs pressed hard for their (Kshatriya) claim. But as is said many times earlier that in the caste federal system of India, changes seldom occur and in case of untouchables or scheduled castes as also established by M. N. Shrinivas there are no chances at all. So the caste of Jatavs went to a predestined end. It is unfortunate that such a powerful effort (Lynch 1969) could result nothing but the result in other fields were rewarding and exemplary. Jatav elites using cultural sentiments and striking the chord of psyche succeeded pursuing several strategies in getting political successes.<ref name=\"Chandel 1990 51\">{{cite book |title=A Social Force in Politics: Study of Scheduled Castes of U.P. |first=M. P. S. |last=Chandel |publisher=Mittal Publications |year=1990 |isbn=9788170991939 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MEjGvOu90x4C&pg=PA51 |pages=51-52}}</ref>}}\n\nIn the early part of the 20th century, the Jatavs attempted the process of [[sanskritisation]], claiming themselves to be historically of the [[kshatriya]] varna. They gained political expertise by forming associations and by developing a literate cadre of leaders, and they tried to change their position in the caste system through the emulation of upper-caste behavior. As a part of this process, they also claimed not to be Chamars and petitioned the government of the [[British Raj]] to be officially classified differently: disassociating themselves from the Chamar community would, they felt, enhance their acceptance as kshatriya. These claims were not accepted by other castes and, although the government was amenable, no official reclassification as a separate community occurred due to the onset of [[World War II]].<ref>{{Cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=_g-_r-9Oa_sC |title=Structure and Change in Indian Society |editor1-first=Milton |editor1-last=Singer |editor2-first=Bernard S. |editor2-last=Cohn |year=2007 |pages=216\u2013217}}</ref>\n\nAn organisation of young Jatavs, called the Jatav Vir, was formed in [[Agra]] in  1917, and a Jatav Pracharak Sangh was organised in 1924.<ref name=\"Chandel 1990 51\"/> They joined with local [[Bania (caste)|Bania]]s to establish a front and thus one of them won the seat of the mayor in Agra, and another became a member of the [[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Council|Legislative Council]].{{cn|date=May 2018}}\n\nEarlier pressing for the Kshatriya status, the new issues emerged among Jatavs in 1944-45. The Jatavs formed the [[Scheduled Caste Federation]] of Agra having ties with the [[B. R. Ambedkar|Ambedkar]]-led [[All India Scheduled Caste Federation]]. They started recognising themselves as Scheduled Caste and hence \"untouchables\".<ref name=\"Modern\" /> This acceptance is attributed to the protections available to the scheduled castes.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Chandel|first1=M. P. S.|title=A Social Force in Politics: Study of Scheduled Castes of U.P.|date=1990|publisher=Mittal Publications|isbn=978-8-17099-193-9|page=52|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MEjGvOu90x4C&pg=PA51}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Owen Lynch: {{quote|The change is due to the fact that Sanskritisation is no longer as effective a means as is political participation for achieving a change in style of life and a rise in the Indian social system, now composed of both caste and class elements.<ref name=\"Modern\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sQF5-d9BMqcC&pg=PT354 |title=The Modern Anthropology of India: Ethnography, Themes and Theory |publisher=Routledge |first1=Peter |last1=Berger |first2=Frank |last2=Heidemann |year=2013 |isbn=978-1-13406-118-1}}</ref>}}\n\n==Religion==\n\nMany Jatavs became Buddhists in 1956.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rpSxJg_ehnIC&pg=PA95 |title=Bhakti Religion in North India: Community Identity and Political Action |first=David N. |last=Lorenzen |publisher=SUNY Press |year=1995 |page=95}}</ref>  In 1990, many more converted to Buddhism,<ref>{{Cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=mBowAQAAIAAJ&q=jatav+Jat&dq=jatav+Jat&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAzgUahUKEwiB1JmEpuXIAhVjE6YKHXK3CGw |title=The scheduled castes |last=Singh|first=Kumar Suresh|publisher=Anthropological Survey of India|year=1993|page=328|isbn=978-0-19563-254-5}}</ref>{{vague|date=December 2015}} but the majority of Jatavs continue to practise Hinduism.<ref>{{cite book |title=The People of India: Uttar Pradesh |volume=13 |editor-first=Kumar Suresh |editor-last=Singh |year=2005 |page=367}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Dalit communities]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Caste of India}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{use Indian English|date=July 2017}}\n\n'''[[Jatavarman Kulasekaran II|Jatav]]''' are the sub-caste, who are classified as a [[Scheduled Caste]] under modern India's [[Reservation in India|system of positive discrimination]].<ref name=\"Chandel 1990 51\"/>\n\nAccording to the [[2011 Census of India]], the Jatav community of [[Uttar Pradesh]] comprised 54% of that state's total 22,496,047 Scheduled Caste population.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/Jatavs-on-top-of-SC-population-in-UP/articleshow/47931787.cms |title=Jatavs on top of SC population in UP |date=4 July 2015 |work=The Times of India}}</ref> In [[Rajasthan]], the Jatavs form 24% of the Scheduled Caste population.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Scheduled castes in Rajasthan |first=Umesh Kishor |last=Jonwal |journal=CASIR |volume=4 |issue=2 |pages=578-586}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nSome authors have disputed being jatav as lower cast. In the 1920s, Jatavs claimed to be survivors of the ancient war between [[Parashuram]], the legend of the [[Brahmin]]s, and [[Kshatriya]]s, forced into hiding. Their proof of ancestry is a series of correspondences or status similarities between Jatav and other Kshatriya clans. According to Owen Lynch, \"These included identical gotras, and such Kshatriya-like ceremonies as shooting a cannon at weddings and the use of the bow and arrow at the birth [[sa\u1e43sk\u0101ra]]\".<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=_g-_r-9Oa_sC&lpg=PP1&dq=Structure%20and%20Change%20in%20Indian%20Society&pg=PA217 |title=Structure and Change in Indian Society |first=Owen M. |last=Lynch |chapter=The Politics of Untouchability: A Case From Agra |editor1-first=Milton B. |editor1-last=Singer |editor2-first=Bernard S. |editor2-last=Cohn |page=217 |publisher=Transaction Publishers |year=1970 |isbn= 978-0-20236-933-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Reconsidering Untouchability: Chamars and Dalit history in North India |first=Ramnarayan S. |last=Rawat |page=127 |publisher=Indiana University Press |year=2011 |isbn=978-0-253-22262-6 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to M. P. S. Chandel {{quote|Jatavs pressed hard for their (Kshatriya) claim. But as is said many times earlier that in the caste federal system of India, changes seldom occur and in case of untouchables or scheduled castes as also established by M. N. Shrinivas there are no chances at all. So the caste of Jatavs went to a predestined end. It is unfortunate that such a powerful effort (Lynch 1969) could result nothing but the result in other fields were rewarding and exemplary. Jatav elites using cultural sentiments and striking the chord of psyche succeeded pursuing several strategies in getting political successes.<ref name=\"Chandel 1990 51\">{{cite book |title=A Social Force in Politics: Study of Scheduled Castes of U.P. |first=M. P. S. |last=Chandel |publisher=Mittal Publications |year=1990 |isbn=9788170991939 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MEjGvOu90x4C&pg=PA51 |pages=51-52}}</ref>}}\n\nIn the early part of the 20th century, the Jatavs attempted the process of [[sanskritisation]], claiming themselves to be historically of the [[kshatriya]] varna. They gained political expertise by forming associations and by developing a literate cadre of leaders, and they tried to change their position in the caste system through the emulation of upper-caste behavior. As a part of this process, they also claimed not to be Chamars and petitioned the government of the [[British Raj]] to be officially classified differently: disassociating themselves from the Chamar community would, they felt, enhance their acceptance as kshatriya. These claims were not accepted by other castes and, although the government was amenable, no official reclassification as a separate community occurred due to the onset of [[World War II]].<ref>{{Cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=_g-_r-9Oa_sC |title=Structure and Change in Indian Society |editor1-first=Milton |editor1-last=Singer |editor2-first=Bernard S. |editor2-last=Cohn |year=2007 |pages=216\u2013217}}</ref>\n\nAn organisation of young Jatavs, called the Jatav Vir, was formed in [[Agra]] in  1917, and a Jatav Pracharak Sangh was organised in 1924.<ref name=\"Chandel 1990 51\"/> They joined with local [[Bania (caste)|Bania]]s to establish a front and thus one of them won the seat of the mayor in Agra, and another became a member of the [[Uttar Pradesh Legislative Council|Legislative Council]].{{cn|date=May 2018}}\n\nEarlier pressing for the Kshatriya status, the new issues emerged among Jatavs in 1944-45. The Jatavs formed the [[Scheduled Caste Federation]] of Agra having ties with the [[B. R. Ambedkar|Ambedkar]]-led [[All India Scheduled Caste Federation]]. They started recognising themselves as Scheduled Caste and hence \"untouchables\".<ref name=\"Modern\" /> This acceptance is attributed to the protections available to the scheduled castes.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Chandel|first1=M. P. S.|title=A Social Force in Politics: Study of Scheduled Castes of U.P.|date=1990|publisher=Mittal Publications|isbn=978-8-17099-193-9|page=52|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MEjGvOu90x4C&pg=PA51}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Owen Lynch: {{quote|The change is due to the fact that Sanskritisation is no longer as effective a means as is political participation for achieving a change in style of life and a rise in the Indian social system, now composed of both caste and class elements.<ref name=\"Modern\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sQF5-d9BMqcC&pg=PT354 |title=The Modern Anthropology of India: Ethnography, Themes and Theory |publisher=Routledge |first1=Peter |last1=Berger |first2=Frank |last2=Heidemann |year=2013 |isbn=978-1-13406-118-1}}</ref>}}\n\n==Religion==\n\nMany Jatavs became Buddhists in 1956.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rpSxJg_ehnIC&pg=PA95 |title=Bhakti Religion in North India: Community Identity and Political Action |first=David N. |last=Lorenzen |publisher=SUNY Press |year=1995 |page=95}}</ref>  In 1990, many more converted to Buddhism,<ref>{{Cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=mBowAQAAIAAJ&q=jatav+Jat&dq=jatav+Jat&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAzgUahUKEwiB1JmEpuXIAhVjE6YKHXK3CGw |title=The scheduled castes |last=Singh|first=Kumar Suresh|publisher=Anthropological Survey of India|year=1993|page=328|isbn=978-0-19563-254-5}}</ref>{{vague|date=December 2015}} but the majority of Jatavs continue to practise Hinduism.<ref>{{cite book |title=The People of India: Uttar Pradesh |volume=13 |editor-first=Kumar Suresh |editor-last=Singh |year=2005 |page=367}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Dalit communities]]\n", "name_user": "PawanjiGupta", "label": "safe", "comment": "Link removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jatav"}
{"title_page": "Dik Manusch", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name                 = Dik Manusch\n| type                 = Street newspaper\n| foundation           = {{start date|2015}}\n| language             = [[Swedish language]]\n| editor               = Britt-Inger Lundqvist,<ref>{{cite news |last=Saha |first=Catarina |date=11 February 2015 |title=K\u00f6p inte tiggarnas tidning i Ume\u00e5 |url=http://www.vk.se/1383717/kop-inte-tiggarnas-tidning-i-umea |newspaper=[[V\u00e4sterbottens-Kuriren]] |language=Swedish |location=[[Ume\u00e5]] |access-date=19 March 2015 }}</ref> Helen Hugosson Strandemo<ref>{{cite news |last=Sykes |first=Abigail |date=9 December 2014 |title=Ny gatutidning f\u00f6r EU-migranter |url=http://www.landetsfria.se/artikel/116175 |newspaper=Landets Fria ([[:sv:Fria Tidningar|sv]]) |language=Swedish |location=[[Stockholm]] |access-date=19 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304083954/http://www.landetsfria.se/artikel/116175 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| ceased publication = {{End date|2017}}\n}}\n\n'''''Dik Manusch''''' ([[Romani language|Romani]]: ''See the Person'', ''Se m\u00e4nniskan'' translated to [[Swedish language|Swedish]])<ref>{{cite news |last=Westberg |first=Fredrik |date=4 March 2015 |title=Virkar mattor i st\u00e4llet f\u00f6r att tigga |url=http://www.op.se/jamtland/ostersund/virkar-mattor-i-stallet-for-att-tigga |newspaper=[[\u00d6stersunds-Posten]] |language=Swedish |location=[[\u00d6stersund]] |access-date=19 March 2015 }}</ref> was a [[street newspaper]] published in northern [[Sweden]]. First published in early 2015 and focused on the [[V\u00e4sterbotten]] province, the newspaper aimed to help homeless [[European Union]] migrants \u2013 who are primarily [[Romani people]] from the [[Balkans]], especially [[Romania]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Berglund |first=Stina |date=26 February 2014 |title=Romerna lever i total mis\u00e4r \u2013 i hela Sverige |url=http://www.etc.se/inrikes/romerna-lever-i-total-misar-i-hela-sverige |newspaper=ETC ([[:sv:ETC (tidskrift)|sv]]) |language=Swedish |location=[[Stockholm]] |access-date=19 March 2015 }}</ref> \u2013 to support themselves by providing an alternative to begging on the streets.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sandgren |first=G\u00f6ran |date=12 January 2015 |title=Tidning ska hj\u00e4lpa tiggare |url=http://www.svt.se/nyheter/regionalt/vasterbottensnytt/tidning-ska-hjalpa-tiggare |newspaper=[[Sveriges Television]], [[V\u00e4sterbottensnytt]] |language=Swedish |location=[[Ume\u00e5]] |access-date=19 March 2015 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402135654/http://www.svt.se/nyheter/regionalt/vasterbottensnytt/tidning-ska-hjalpa-tiggare |archivedate=2 April 2015 |df= }}</ref> Distributed for free to the migrants, each newspaper was sold for 50 [[Swedish krona]], the profits going entirely to the seller.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ahlqvist |first=Oskar |date=13 March 2015 |title=Webb-TV: Kabar\u00e9 till st\u00f6d f\u00f6r heml\u00f6sa |url=http://www.kuriren.nu/kultur/kabar-till-stod-for-hemlosa-8172957.aspx |newspaper=[[Norrbottens-Kuriren]] |language=Swedish |location=[[Lule\u00e5]] |access-date=19 March 2015 }}</ref> A second purpose was to create a debate in Swedish society about the conditions faced by these people.<ref>{{cite news |last=Apel R\u00f6stlund |first=Johan |date=10 January 2015 |title=Vi vill skapa j\u00e4mb\u00f6rdiga m\u00f6ten |url=http://arbetaren.se/artiklar/vi-vill-skapa-jambordiga-moten/ |newspaper=[[Arbetaren]] |language=Swedish |location=[[Stockholm]] |access-date=19 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nPreparations for the newspaper began in 2014, on suggestion from Ilile Dumitru, who had seen ''[[Situation Sthlm]]'' being sold by the homeless of [[Stockholm]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Lundstr\u00f6m |first=Emma |date=18 March 2015 |title=Rapport fr\u00e5n ett husvagnsl\u00e4ger |url=http://www.internationalen.se/2015/03/rapport-fran-ett-husvagnslager/ |newspaper=[[Internationalen]] |language=Swedish |location=[[Stockholm]] |access-date=19 March 2015 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402144526/http://www.internationalen.se/2015/03/rapport-fran-ett-husvagnslager/ |archivedate=2 April 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wemmenhed |first=Ulrik |date=19 December 2014 |title=Ny tidning f\u00f6rs\u00f6ker \u00f6verbrygga en maktobalans |url=https://feministisktperspektiv.se/2014/12/19/ny-tidning-forsoker-overbrygga-en-maktobalans/ |newspaper=Feministiskt Perspektiv ([[:sv:Feministiskt Perspektiv|sv]]) |language=Swedish |location=[[Stockholm]] |access-date=19 March 2015 }}</ref> The newspaper was created by the association SAMS, a coalition of several different organizations and churches in [[Skellefte\u00e5]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Bergner |first=Magnus |date=12 January 2015 |title=Premi\u00e4r idag f\u00f6r tiggarnas tidning Dik Manusch |url=http://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=109&artikel=6065460 |newspaper=[[Sveriges Radio]], P4 V\u00e4sterbotten ([[:sv:P4 V\u00e4sterbotten|sv]]) |language=Swedish |location=[[Ume\u00e5]] |access-date=19 March 2015 }}</ref> The first issue \u2013 numbering 5,000 \u2013 was printed by ''[[Norran]]'', and featured content created by various writers on a non-profit basis.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ekman |first=Mats |date=2 January 2015 |title=Chans att f\u00e5 veta mer om tiggarna |url=http://norran.se/nyheter/chans-att-fa-veta-mer-om-tiggarna-2-328544 |newspaper=[[Norran]] |language=Swedish |location=[[Skellefte\u00e5]] |access-date=19 March 2015 }}</ref> The second issue, with 15,000 prints, was likewise printed by ''Norran'' and financed by volunteer donations. To support the newspaper an association called the ''Dik Manusch V\u00e4nner'' (''Friends of Dik Manusch'' in English) was formed.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bergner |first=Magnus |date=3 May 2015 |title=Andra numret av Dik Manusch ute |url=http://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=109&artikel=6155989 |newspaper=[[Sveriges Radio]], P4 V\u00e4sterbotten ([[:sv:P4 V\u00e4sterbotten|sv]])  |language=Swedish |location=[[Ume\u00e5]] |access-date=27 May 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn the beginning of 2017, the editorial staff came to the conclusion that they no longer got enough content sent in to be able to publish an issue.<ref name=\"SR P4 V\u00e4sterbotten - 2017-06-24\"/> A few months later it was decided to disband the association and to cease publishing the newspaper.<ref name=\"SR P4 V\u00e4sterbotten - 2017-06-24\"/><ref name=\"SR P4 V\u00e4sterbotten - 2017-07-26\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Journalism|Sweden}}\n\n* ''[[Aluma (street paper)|Aluma]]''\n* [[Begging]]\n* ''[[Faktum]]''\n\n==References==\n<references>\n<ref name=\"SR P4 V\u00e4sterbotten - 2017-06-24\">{{cite news\n  |last = Lindberg\n  |first = Hjalmar\n  |date = 24 June 2017\n  |title = Tidningen Dik Manusch l\u00e4gger ner\n  |trans-title = The newspaper Dik Manusch ceases operations\n  |url = https://sverigesradio.se/artikel/6723986\n  |url-status = live\n  |website = [[Sveriges Radio]]\n  |language = Swedish\n  |access-date = 10 April 2020\n  |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200410173738/https://sverigesradio.se/artikel/6723986\n  |archive-date = 10 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"SR P4 V\u00e4sterbotten - 2017-07-26\">{{cite news\n  |last = Tajik\n  |first = Amir\n  |date = 26 July 2017\n  |title = Tidningen Dik Manusch l\u00e4ggs ner\n  |trans-title = The newspaper Dik Manusch ceases operations\n  |url = https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=98&artikel=6744702\n  |url-status = live\n  |website = [[Sveriges Radio]]\n  |language = Swedish\n  |access-date = 10 April 2020\n  |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200410173438/https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=98&artikel=6744702\n  |archive-date = 10 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n</references>\n\n== External links ==\n{{webarchive\n  |url = http://web.archive.org/web/20161129173630/http://dik-manusch.tk/\n  |date = 29 November 2016\n  |title= Official website {{in lang|sv}}}}\n\n{{Romani diaspora}}\n{{Street newspapers}}\n\n[[Category:Street newspapers]]\n[[Category:Swedish-language newspapers]]\n[[Category:Defunct newspapers of Sweden]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Publications disestablished in 2017]]\n[[Category:2015 establishments in Sweden]]\n[[Category:2017 disestablishments in Sweden]]\n\n{{Sweden-newspaper-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name                 = Dik Manusch\n| type                 = Street newspaper\n| foundation           = {{start date|2015}}\n| language             = [[Swedish language]]\n| editor               = Britt-Inger Lundqvist,<ref>{{cite news |last=Saha |first=Catarina |date=11 February 2015 |title=K\u00f6p inte tiggarnas tidning i Ume\u00e5 |url=http://www.vk.se/1383717/kop-inte-tiggarnas-tidning-i-umea |newspaper=[[V\u00e4sterbottens-Kuriren]] |language=Swedish |location=[[Ume\u00e5]] |access-date=19 March 2015 }}</ref> Helen Hugosson Strandemo<ref>{{cite news |last=Sykes |first=Abigail |date=9 December 2014 |title=Ny gatutidning f\u00f6r EU-migranter |url=http://www.landetsfria.se/artikel/116175 |newspaper=Landets Fria ([[:sv:Fria Tidningar|sv]]) |language=Swedish |location=[[Stockholm]] |access-date=19 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304083954/http://www.landetsfria.se/artikel/116175 |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| ceased publication = {{End date|2017}}\n}}\n\n'''''Dik Manusch''''' ([[Romani language|Romani]]: ''See the Person'', ''Se m\u00e4nniskan'' translated to [[Swedish language|Swedish]])<ref>{{cite news |last=Westberg |first=Fredrik |date=4 March 2015 |title=Virkar mattor i st\u00e4llet f\u00f6r att tigga |url=http://www.op.se/jamtland/ostersund/virkar-mattor-i-stallet-for-att-tigga |newspaper=[[\u00d6stersunds-Posten]] |language=Swedish |location=[[\u00d6stersund]] |access-date=19 March 2015 }}</ref> was a [[street newspaper]] published in northern [[Sweden]]. First published in early 2015 and focused on the [[V\u00e4sterbotten]] province, the newspaper aimed to help homeless [[European Union]] migrants \u2013 who are primarily [[Romani people]] from the [[Balkans]], especially [[Romania]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Berglund |first=Stina |date=26 February 2014 |title=Romerna lever i total mis\u00e4r \u2013 i hela Sverige |url=http://www.etc.se/inrikes/romerna-lever-i-total-misar-i-hela-sverige |newspaper=ETC ([[:sv:ETC (tidskrift)|sv]]) |language=Swedish |location=[[Stockholm]] |access-date=19 March 2015 }}</ref> \u2013 to support themselves by providing an alternative to begging on the streets.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sandgren |first=G\u00f6ran |date=12 January 2015 |title=Tidning ska hj\u00e4lpa tiggare |url=http://www.svt.se/nyheter/regionalt/vasterbottensnytt/tidning-ska-hjalpa-tiggare |newspaper=[[Sveriges Television]], [[V\u00e4sterbottensnytt]] |language=Swedish |location=[[Ume\u00e5]] |access-date=19 March 2015 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402135654/http://www.svt.se/nyheter/regionalt/vasterbottensnytt/tidning-ska-hjalpa-tiggare |archivedate=2 April 2015 |df= }}</ref> Distributed for free to the migrants, each newspaper was sold for 50 [[Swedish krona]], the profits going entirely to the seller.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ahlqvist |first=Oskar |date=13 March 2015 |title=Webb-TV: Kabar\u00e9 till st\u00f6d f\u00f6r heml\u00f6sa |url=http://www.kuriren.nu/kultur/kabar-till-stod-for-hemlosa-8172957.aspx |newspaper=[[Norrbottens-Kuriren]] |language=Swedish |location=[[Lule\u00e5]] |access-date=19 March 2015 }}</ref> A second purpose was to create a debate in Swedish society about the conditions faced by these people.<ref>{{cite news |last=Apel R\u00f6stlund |first=Johan |date=10 January 2015 |title=Vi vill skapa j\u00e4mb\u00f6rdiga m\u00f6ten |url=http://arbetaren.se/artiklar/vi-vill-skapa-jambordiga-moten/ |newspaper=[[Arbetaren]] |language=Swedish |location=[[Stockholm]] |access-date=19 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nPreparations for the newspaper began in 2014, on suggestion from Ilile Dumitru, who had seen ''[[Situation Sthlm]]'' being sold by the homeless of [[Stockholm]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Lundstr\u00f6m |first=Emma |date=18 March 2015 |title=Rapport fr\u00e5n ett husvagnsl\u00e4ger |url=http://www.internationalen.se/2015/03/rapport-fran-ett-husvagnslager/ |newspaper=[[Internationalen]] |language=Swedish |location=[[Stockholm]] |access-date=19 March 2015 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402144526/http://www.internationalen.se/2015/03/rapport-fran-ett-husvagnslager/ |archivedate=2 April 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wemmenhed |first=Ulrik |date=19 December 2014 |title=Ny tidning f\u00f6rs\u00f6ker \u00f6verbrygga en maktobalans |url=https://feministisktperspektiv.se/2014/12/19/ny-tidning-forsoker-overbrygga-en-maktobalans/ |newspaper=Feministiskt Perspektiv ([[:sv:Feministiskt Perspektiv|sv]]) |language=Swedish |location=[[Stockholm]] |access-date=19 March 2015 }}</ref> The newspaper was created by the association SAMS, a coalition of several different organizations and churches in [[Skellefte\u00e5]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Bergner |first=Magnus |date=12 January 2015 |title=Premi\u00e4r idag f\u00f6r tiggarnas tidning Dik Manusch |url=http://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=109&artikel=6065460 |newspaper=[[Sveriges Radio]], P4 V\u00e4sterbotten ([[:sv:P4 V\u00e4sterbotten|sv]]) |language=Swedish |location=[[Ume\u00e5]] |access-date=19 March 2015 }}</ref> The first issue \u2013 numbering 5,000 \u2013 was printed by ''[[Norran]]'', and featured content created by various writers on a non-profit basis.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ekman |first=Mats |date=2 January 2015 |title=Chans att f\u00e5 veta mer om tiggarna |url=http://norran.se/nyheter/chans-att-fa-veta-mer-om-tiggarna-2-328544 |newspaper=[[Norran]] |language=Swedish |location=[[Skellefte\u00e5]] |access-date=19 March 2015 }}</ref> The second issue, with 15,000 prints, was likewise printed by ''Norran'' and financed by volunteer donations. To support the newspaper an association called the ''Dik Manusch V\u00e4nner'' (''Friends of Dik Manusch'' in English) was formed.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bergner |first=Magnus |date=3 May 2015 |title=Andra numret av Dik Manusch ute |url=http://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=109&artikel=6155989 |newspaper=[[Sveriges Radio]], P4 V\u00e4sterbotten ([[:sv:P4 V\u00e4sterbotten|sv]])  |language=Swedish |location=[[Ume\u00e5]] |access-date=27 May 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn the beginning of 2017, the editorial staff came to the conclusion that they no longer got enough content sent in to be able to publish an issue.<ref name=\"SR P4 V\u00e4sterbotten - 2017-06-24\"/> A few months later it was decided to disband the association and to cease publishing the newspaper.<ref name=\"SR P4 V\u00e4sterbotten - 2017-06-24\"/><ref name=\"SR P4 V\u00e4sterbotten - 2017-07-26\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Journalism|Sweden}}\n\n* ''[[Aluma (street paper)|Aluma]]''\n* [[Begging]]\n* ''[[Faktum]]''\n\n==References==\n<references>\n<ref name=\"SR P4 V\u00e4sterbotten - 2017-06-24\">{{cite news\n  |last = Lindberg\n  |first = Hjalmar\n  |date = 24 June 2017\n  |title = Tidningen Dik Manusch l\u00e4gger ner\n  |trans-title = The newspaper Dik Manusch ceases operations\n  |url = https://sverigesradio.se/artikel/6723986\n  |url-status = live\n  |website = [[Sveriges Radio]]\n  |language = Swedish\n  |access-date = 10 April 2020\n  |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200410173738/https://sverigesradio.se/artikel/6723986\n  |archive-date = 10 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"SR P4 V\u00e4sterbotten - 2017-07-26\">{{cite news\n  |last = Tajik\n  |first = Amir\n  |date = 26 July 2017\n  |title = Tidningen Dik Manusch l\u00e4ggs ner\n  |trans-title = The newspaper Dik Manusch ceases operations\n  |url = https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.a