{"title_page": "Ratnamanirao Jote", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}}\n'''Ratnamanirao Jhote ''' was an Indian historian who wrote extensively on the [[History of Gujarat|history]] and [[Culture of Gujarat|culture]] of [[Gujarat]].\n\n==Life==\nRatnamanirao Bhimrao Jhote was born on 19 October 1895 at [[Bhuj]] to Dewan Motilal Lalbhai. He was nicknamed Bhanabhai by his family. He was born prematurely. His maternal home was in Sankali Sheri in [[Khadia]], [[Ahmedabad]]. During his childhood, he used to publish handwritten weekly ''Ghar Samachar'' for his home in which he used to write a title article, about family members, \"missing\" items and a Gujarati translation of an English novel. He started his primary education in English from Middle Highschool in [[Bhadra Fort|Bhadra]] area. Later he joined R. C. Highschool where he completed his matriculation in 1914. He completed B. A. in Sanskrit and English from [[Gujarat College]] in 1919. He joined business firm dealing in cloth and cotton yarn.<ref name=\"Yagnik2011\">{{cite book|author=Achyut Yagnik|title=Ahmedabad: From Royal city to Megacity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ivMAUx6Hdl8C&pg=PT7|date=2 February 2011|publisher=Penguin Books Limited|isbn=978-81-8475-473-5|page=7}}</ref> He had close relationship with [[Sir Chinubhai Madhowlal Ranchhodlal, 1st Baronet|Sir Chinubhai Baronet]] and [[Anandshankar Dhruv]].<ref name=\"WG2015\">{{cite web | title=\u0a87\u0aa4\u0abf\u0ab9\u0abe\u0ab8\u0a95\u0abe\u0ab0 \u0ab0\u0aa4\u0acd\u0aa8\u0aae\u0aa3\u0abf\u0ab0\u0abe\u0ab5 \u0a9c\u0acb\u0a9f\u0ac7\u0aa8\u0ac0 \u0a85\u0a82\u0aa4\u0ab0\u0a82\u0a97 \u0ab5\u0abe\u0aa4\u0acb|author=Mehboob Desai | website=Webgurjari | date=22 September 2015 | url=http://webgurjari.in/2015/09/22/historian-ratnamanirao-jotes-intimated-details/ | language=gu | accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe received attention when he wrote an article, ''Gujaratni Sanskriti Ane Itihasnu Vihangavlokan'' (Bird's View of Culture and History of Gujarat). Initially he wrote research articles in ''Kumar'' magazine. He did research on [[Somnath temple]] when it was re-erected by [[Vallabhbhai Patel]].<ref name=\"WG2015\"/>\n\nHe died after prolonged illness around 3:30 pm on 24 September 1955.<ref name=\"WG2015\"/>\n\n== Works ==\nApart from history and culture, he wrote plays, poems and on astrology.\n\n=== History ===\n* ''Amdavadno Parichay'' (Introduction of Ahmedabad) \n* ''[[Khambhat]]<nowiki/>no Itihas'' (History of Cambay; 1935) \n* ''Gujaratno Sanskrutik Itihas'' (Cultural History of Gujarat) \n* ''Gujaratnu Vahanvatu'' (Maritime History of Gujarat) \n* ''Gujaratnu Patnagar Amdavad'' (Ahmedabad: Capital of Gujarat; 1929)<ref name=\"Vashi 2008\">{{cite web | last=Vashi | first=Ashish | title=Garba songs are slices of history | website=The Times of India | date=1 October 2008 | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Garba-songs-are-slices-of-history/articleshow/3546617.cms | accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"toin2011\">{{cite web | title=Bapu had a dream for Amdavad  | website=[[The Times of India]] | date=17 April 2011 | url=http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=pastissues2&BaseHref=TOIA/2011/04/17&PageLabel=2&EntityId=Ar00200&ViewMode=HTML | accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Livemint 2011\">{{cite web | title=Tides of the Sabarmati | website=Livemint | date=4 March 2011 | url=http://www.livemint.com/Leisure/45WflMciTmVFFoDxXhBo1L/Tides-of-the-Sabarmati.html | accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n* ''Gujaratno Sanskrutik Itihas Islam Yug'' (Cultural History of Gujarat: Islamic Era, Four Volumes)<ref name=\"divyabhaskar 2011\">{{cite web | title=\u0a86\u0aaa\u0aa3\u0acb \u0ab8\u0abe\u0a82\u0ab8\u0acd\u0a95\u0ac3\u0aa4\u0abf\u0a95 \u0ab5\u0abe\u0ab0\u0ab8\u0acb \u0a9b\u0ac7 \u0aae\u0aa7\u0acd\u0aaf\u0a95\u0abe\u0ab2\u0ac0\u0aa8 \u0a85\u0aae\u0aa6\u0abe\u0ab5\u0abe\u0aa6\u0aa8\u0ac0 \u0aae\u0ab8\u0acd\u0a9c\u0abf\u0aa6\u0acb | website=[[Divya Bhaskar]]|author=Mehboob Desai | date=14 July 2011 | url=http://www.divyabhaskar.co.in/news/MAG-rahe-roshan-dr-mehboob-desai-ahmedabad-masjid-2260941.html | language=gu | accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[Somnath]]'' (1949)\n* ''Amdavadnun Sthapatya : Eno Itihas Ane Samnya Ruprekha'' (Architecture of Ahmedabad: Its History and Timeline; 1929)\n\n=== Others ===\nHe translated ''[[The Admirable Crichton]]'' by [[J. M. Barrie]] as a Gujarati play ''Sambhavit Sundarlal'' (1940). It had two-three shows.<ref name=\"WG2015\"/>\n\n== Recognition ==\nHe was awarded [[Ranjitram Suvarna Chandrak]] in 1933.<ref name=\"WG2015\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jote, Ratnamanirao}}\n[[Category:Gujarati-language writers]]\n[[Category:People from Bhuj\u200e]]\n[[Category:Writers from Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian historians]]\n[[Category:1955 deaths]]\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Ranjitram Suvarna Chandrak]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}}\n'''Ratnamanirao Jhote ''' was an Indian historian who wrote extensively on the [[History of Gujarat|history]] and [[Culture of Gujarat|culture]] of [[Gujarat]].\n\n==Life==\nRatnamanirao Bhimrao Jhote was born on 19 October 1895 at [[Bhuj]] to Dewan Motilal Lalbhai. He was nicknamed Bhanabhai by his family. He was born prematurely. His maternal home was in Sankali Sheri in [[Khadia]], [[Ahmedabad]]. During his childhood, he used to publish handwritten weekly ''Ghar Samachar'' for his home in which he used to write a title article, about family members, \"missing\" items and a Gujarati translation of an English novel. He started his primary education in English from Middle Highschool in [[Bhadra Fort|Bhadra]] area. Later he joined R. C. Highschool where he completed his matriculation in 1914. He completed B. A. in Sanskrit and English from [[Gujarat College]] in 1919. He joined business firm dealing in cloth and cotton yarn.<ref name=\"Yagnik2011\">{{cite book|author=Achyut Yagnik|title=Ahmedabad: From Royal city to Megacity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ivMAUx6Hdl8C&pg=PT7|date=2 February 2011|publisher=Penguin Books Limited|isbn=978-81-8475-473-5|page=7}}</ref> He had close relationship with [[Sir Chinubhai Madhowlal Ranchhodlal, 1st Baronet|Sir Chinubhai Baronet]] and [[Anandshankar Dhruv]].<ref name=\"WG2015\">{{cite web | title=\u0a87\u0aa4\u0abf\u0ab9\u0abe\u0ab8\u0a95\u0abe\u0ab0 \u0ab0\u0aa4\u0acd\u0aa8\u0aae\u0aa3\u0abf\u0ab0\u0abe\u0ab5 \u0a9c\u0acb\u0a9f\u0ac7\u0aa8\u0ac0 \u0a85\u0a82\u0aa4\u0ab0\u0a82\u0a97 \u0ab5\u0abe\u0aa4\u0acb|author=Mehboob Desai | website=Webgurjari | date=22 September 2015 | url=http://webgurjari.in/2015/09/22/historian-ratnamanirao-jotes-intimated-details/ | language=gu | accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe received attention when he wrote an article, ''Gujaratni Sanskriti Ane Itihasnu Vihangavlokan'' (Bird's View of Culture and History of Gujarat). Initially he wrote research articles in ''Kumar'' magazine. He did research on [[Somnath temple]] when it was re-erected by [[Vallabhbhai Patel]].<ref name=\"WG2015\"/>\n\nHe died after prolonged illness around 3:30 pm on 24 September 1955.<ref name=\"WG2015\"/>\n\n== Works ==\nApart from history and culture, he wrote plays, poems and on astrology.\n\n=== History ===\n* ''Amdavadno Parichay'' (Introduction of Ahmedabad) \n* ''[[Khambhat]]<nowiki/>no Itihas'' (History of Cambay; 1935) \n* ''Gujaratno Sanskrutik Itihas'' (Cultural History of Gujarat) \n* ''Gujaratnu Vahanvatu'' (Maritime History of Gujarat) \n* ''Gujaratnu Patnagar Amdavad'' (Ahmedabad: Capital of Gujarat; 1929)<ref name=\"Vashi 2008\">{{cite web | last=Vashi | first=Ashish | title=Garba songs are slices of history | website=The Times of India | date=1 October 2008 | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Garba-songs-are-slices-of-history/articleshow/3546617.cms | accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"toin2011\">{{cite web | title=Bapu had a dream for Amdavad  | website=[[The Times of India]] | date=17 April 2011 | url=http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=pastissues2&BaseHref=TOIA/2011/04/17&PageLabel=2&EntityId=Ar00200&ViewMode=HTML | accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Livemint 2011\">{{cite web | title=Tides of the Sabarmati | website=Livemint | date=4 March 2011 | url=http://www.livemint.com/Leisure/45WflMciTmVFFoDxXhBo1L/Tides-of-the-Sabarmati.html | accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n* ''Gujaratno Sanskrutik Itihas Islam Yug'' (Cultural History of Gujarat: Islamic Era, Four Volumes)<ref name=\"divyabhaskar 2011\">{{cite web | title=\u0a86\u0aaa\u0aa3\u0acb \u0ab8\u0abe\u0a82\u0ab8\u0acd\u0a95\u0ac3\u0aa4\u0abf\u0a95 \u0ab5\u0abe\u0ab0\u0ab8\u0acb \u0a9b\u0ac7 \u0aae\u0aa7\u0acd\u0aaf\u0a95\u0abe\u0ab2\u0ac0\u0aa8 \u0a85\u0aae\u0aa6\u0abe\u0ab5\u0abe\u0aa6\u0aa8\u0ac0 \u0aae\u0ab8\u0acd\u0a9c\u0abf\u0aa6\u0acb | website=[[Divya Bhaskar]]|author=Mehboob Desai | date=14 July 2011 | url=http://www.divyabhaskar.co.in/news/MAG-rahe-roshan-dr-mehboob-desai-ahmedabad-masjid-2260941.html | language=gu | accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[Somnath]]'' (1949)\n* ''Amdavadnun Sthapatya : Eno Itihas Ane Samnya Ruprekha'' (Architecture of Ahmedabad: Its History and Timeline; 1929)\n\n=== Others ===\nHe translated ''[[The Admirable Crichton]]'' by [[J. M. Barrie]] as a Gujarati play ''Sambhavit Sundarlal'' (1940). It had two-three shows.<ref name=\"WG2015\"/>\n\n== Recognition ==\nHe was awarded [[Ranjitram Suvarna Chandrak]] in 1933.<ref name=\"WG2015\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jote, Ratnamanirao}}\n[[Category:Gujarati-language writers]]\n[[Category:People from Kutch district]]\n[[Category:Writers from Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian historians]]\n[[Category:1955 deaths]]\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Ranjitram Suvarna Chandrak]]\n", "name_user": "Jaywardhan009", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ratnamanirao_Jote"}
